{"title_page": "Hartington Upper Quarter", "text_new": "'''Hartington Upper Quarter''' is a [[civil parish]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Harrington Upper Quarter Parish Council|url=http://hartingtonupperquarter-pc.org|website=www.hartingtonupperquarter-pc.org|publisher=Harrington Upper Quarter Parish Council|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> in the [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]] district of [[Derbyshire]], England.<ref name=OSelec>{{cite web|url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/election-maps/gb/# |title=Ordnance Survey Election Maps|website=www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk |publisher=Ordnance Survey |accessdate=18 February 2016}}</ref> The civil parish was created following the division of the ancient parish of [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]] into four.  The parish had a population of 451 according to the 2001 census reducing to 438 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11124274&c=Hartington&d=16&e=62&g=6414192&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1458921610083&enc=1|title=Hartington Upper Quarter population 2011|accessdate=25 March 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nThe parish is long and thin, extending from north-west of Buxton, taking in the [[Errwood Reservoir]], to the south-east, and [[Ann Croft]].  The parish borders parishes in High Peak and [[Derbyshire Dales]] districts, and also some parishes in the [[Staffordshire Moorlands]] and [[Cheshire East]] districts.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|53.2748|-1.9767|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Derbyshire]]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Hartington Upper Quarter''' is a [[civil parish]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Harrington Upper Quarter Parish Council|url=http://hartingtonupperquarter-pc.org|website=www.hartingtonupperquarter-pc.org|publisher=Harrington Upper Quarter Parish Council|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> in the [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]] district of [[Derbyshire]], England.<ref name=OSelec>{{cite web|url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/election-maps/gb/# |title=Ordnance Survey Election Maps|website=www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk |publisher=Ordnance Survey |accessdate=18 February 2016}}</ref> The civil parish was created following the division of the ancient parish of [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]] into four.  The parish had a population of 451 according to the 2001 census reducing to 438 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11124274&c=Hartington&d=16&e=62&g=6414192&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1458921610083&enc=1|title=Hartington Upper Quarter population 2011|accessdate=25 March 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nThe parish is long and thin, extending from north-west of Buxton, taking in the [[Errwood Reservoir]], to the south-east, and [[Ann Croft]].  The parish borders parishes in High Peak and [[Derbyshire Dales]] districts, and also some parishes in the [[Staffordshire Moorlands]] and [[Cheshire East]] districts.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|53.2748|-1.9767|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Derbyshire]]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak, Derbyshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hartington_Upper_Quarter"}
{"title_page": "Rhinoceros Party of Canada candidates in the 1980 Canadian federal election", "text_new": "The first and original '''[[Rhinoceros Party of Canada (1963\u20131993)|Rhinoceros Party of Canada]]''' fielded 116 candidates in the '''[[1980 Canadian federal election|1980 federal election]]''', none of whom were elected. One candidate finished second. One finished third. Some who finished fourth beat the [[New Democratic Party|NDP]], and are mentioned. Others who placed fourth beat [[Social Credit Party of Canada|Social Credit]], there were only four candidates on the ballot, or there was a wide field of fringe parties.\n\n==[[Alberta]]==\nAll Alberta Rhino candidates but one came in fourth, for a number of reasons.\n===Samoil, Willy ([[Calgary Centre]]) 766 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Pazdor, Philip J. ([[Calgary East]]) 638 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Williams, Mike ([[Calgary North]]) 878 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Lambe, David E. Fred ([[Calgary South]]) 887 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Petti, Anthony G. ([[Calgary West]]) 1,027 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Walker, Dave ([[Edmonton_Strathcona|Edmonton-Strathcona]]) 453 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Cavanagh, Allan G. W. ([[Peace_River_(electoral_district)|Peace River]]) 547 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Hohol, Carl M. ([[Vegreville_(electoral_district)|Vegreville]]) 359 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n==[[British Columbia]]==\nB.C. Rhino candidates generally ran against a wide field of minority parties and independent candidates. They came fourth in all but one riding contested.\n===Schaller, Richard The Troll ([[Capilano_(electoral_district)|Capilano]]) 688 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Lesosky, Louis Crowbird ([[Cowichan\u2014Malahat\u2014The_Islands|Cowichan-Malhat-The Islands]]) 444 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Maddocks, Bob ([[Esquimalt\u2014Saanich|Esquimalt-Saanich]]) 548 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n===Storey, Kyle ([[Kamloops-Shuswap]]) 237 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Coffey, Frank Tee Pee Red ([[Nanaimo-Alberni]]) 591 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Kruger, Andre The Rock ([[Okanagan-Similkameen]]) 317 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n===Courchene, Albert The Cad ([[Surrey\u2014White_Rock\u2014North_Delta|Surrey-White Rock-North Delta]]) 440 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Longworth, David J. ([[Vancouver Centre]]) 337 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Lyttle, Dandy Randy ([[Vancouver East]]) 198 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===McDonald, Verne John Eh ([[Vancouver Quadra]]) 405 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Fleming, Linda ([[Vancouver South]]) 327 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Higgins, Rhino Kirk ([[Victoria_(electoral_district)|Victoria]]) 446 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n==[[Manitoba]]==\nManitoban Rhino candidates were generally uncontested for fourth.\n===Campbell, Roland ([[Churchill\u2014Keewatinook_Aski|[formerly] Churchill]]) 352 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Feilburg, Lawrence ([[Provencher]]) 433 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Bergen, Honest Don ([[Winnipeg\u2014Birds_Hill|Winnipeg-Birds Hill]]) 322 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Balderstone, Smilin Dave ([[Winnipeg\u2014Fort_Garry|Winnipeg-Fort Garry]]) 405 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n==[[New Brunswick]]==\n===Boucher, Amede Le Terrible ([[Acadie\u2014Bathurst| [formerly] Gloucester]]) 362 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n===Boudreau, Jules Cesar ([[Acadie\u2014Bathurst|[formerly] Gloucester]]) 736 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nBoth candidates combined and Boudreau himself ranked 4th.\n===Doucet, Arthur ([[Restigouche_(electoral_district)|Restigouche]]) 692 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n==[[Nova Scotia]]==\n===Moors, Mark ([[Kings\u2014Hants|[formerly] Annapolis Valley-Hants]]) 343 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Tudor, Martha ([[South_Shore\u2014St._Margarets|[formerly] South Shore]]) 433 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n==[[Ontario]]==\n===Reid, David J. ([[Beaches_(electoral_district)|Beaches]]) 214 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Butterfield, Vicki ([[Toronto\u2014Danforth|[formerly] Broadview\u2014Greenwood]])===\nButterfield, wife of noted computer expert [[Jim Butterfield]],<ref name=\"hooktorpet\" /> ran a low-profile campaign.  The Rhinoceros Party announced that she was \"following the lead of another, more prominent candidate, and is hiding from the public\".<ref name=\"vicki\" />  This was likely a reference to [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] leader [[Pierre Trudeau]].  She received 196 votes (0.61%), finishing fourth against [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] incumbent [[Bob Rae]].\n\n===Thorning, Steve ([[Guelph (electoral district)|Guelph]]) 272 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Sabzali, James E. S. ([[Hamilton_West_(Canadian_electoral_district)|Hamilton West]]) 304 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Sharp, Edward T. ([[Kingston and the Islands]]) 373 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Wright, Douglas ([[Kitchener_(electoral_district)|Kitchener]]) 292 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Showers, Stewart ([[London West]]) 224 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Cockerell, Alan ([[Nepean-Carleton]]) 658 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Stranart, J. C. ([[Ontario_(electoral_district)|Ontario]]) 313 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Langille, David ([[Ottawa Centre]]) 358 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Ashby, Graham Prickes ([[Ottawa-Vanier]]) 519 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Elson, Mark ([[Peterborough\u2014Kawartha|[formerly] Peterborough]]) 243 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />=