/>===\nFinished 4th.\n===Theriault, Face-Bleme Jacques ([[Montmorency_(electoral_district)|Montmorency]]) 1,913 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Rivard, Michel Flybin ([[Mount_Royal_(electoral_district)|Mount Royal]]) 715 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Roy, Cherubin Guy ([[Notre-Dame-de-Gr\u00e2ce_(electoral_district)|Notre-Dame-de-Gr\u00e2ce]]) 900 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Langlois, Philippe ([[Outremont_(electoral_district)|Outremont]]) 2,065 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Harvey, La Mule Louis ([[Papineau (electoral district)|Papineau]]) 1,608 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Beauregard, Gaston Lagaffe ([[Pontiac-Gatineau-Labelle]]) 643 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Paquette, J. Chretin ([[Portneuf\u2014Jacques-Cartier|[formerly] Portneuf]]) 1,634 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Pollender, Raymond Patrotrovitch ([[Quebec_East|Qu\u00e9bec-Est]]) 1,862 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Moreau, Helene ([[B\u00e9cancour\u2014Nicolet\u2014Saurel|[formerly] Richelieu]]) 1,215 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Caron, Denys ([[Richmond\u2014Wolfe|Richmond]]) 876 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Saintonge, Jacques ([[Rimouski_(electoral_district)|Rimouski]]) 627 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Simard, Donald Bobette ([[Roberval (electoral district)|Roberval]]) 503 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n===Tremblay, G. Mara ([[Rosemont\u2014La_Petite-Patrie|[formerly] Rosemont]]) 1,310 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Rose, Serge ([[Saint-Denis (electoral district)|Saint-Denis]]) 1,232 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Montpetit, Jean-Guy ([[Saint-Henri-Westmount]]) 1,140 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Chamberland, Andre ([[Saint-Hyacinthe\u2014Bagot|Saint-Hyacinthe]]) 868 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Tremblay, Rodrigue Chocolat ([[Saint-Jacques_(electoral_district)|Saint Jacques]]) 1,080 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Arene, Jean-Luc ([[Saint-Jean (electoral district)|Saint-Jean]]) 982 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n===Guzzo-Ceros ([[Saint-Leonard-Anjou]]) 1,569 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Favreau, Francois Straight ([[Sainte-Marie_(electoral_district)|Sainte-Marie]]) 1,659 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===De Vernal, J. F. Le Calife ([[Saint-Maurice (electoral district)|Saint-Maurice]]) 1,206 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n===Chaput, Benoit Yodepech ([[Saint-Michel_(electoral_district)|Saint-Michel]]) 1,603 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Brazeau, Cornelius Andre ([[Shefford_(electoral_district)|Shefford]]) 1,274 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Bedard, Fernand ([[Sherbrooke_(electoral_district)|Sherbrooke]]) 909 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Massicotte, Michel Celestin ([[Abitibi\u2014T\u00e9miscamingue|[formerly] Temiscamingue]]) 1,206 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Drapeau, Pedro Gervais G. D. ([[Terrebonne_(electoral_district)|Terrebonne]]) 1,844 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\n\n===Mignault, Hughe Le Brulot ([[Verch\u00e8res_(electoral_district)|Vercheres]]) 2,804 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n===Cawthorn, Ronald ([[Verdun_(electoral_district)|Verdun]]) 1,141 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n==[[Saskatchewan]]==\n===Bowden, Ross Dunning ([[Kindersley-Lloydminster]]) 294 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n===Hoover, Derron H. X. ([[Regina East]]) 302 votes <ref name=\"EC\" />===\nFinished 4th.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"hooktorpet\">{{cite journal\n  |author=Hook, Gail\n  | date=September 1982 |title=TPUG's Grandfather: Getting Acquainted with Jim Butterfield\n  |url=http://www.tpug.ca/tpug-media/torpet/Torpet_Issue_13_1982_Sep.pdf\n  |journal=[[The TORPET]]\n  |publisher=[[Toronto PET Users Group]]\n  |volume=\n  |issue=13\n  |pages=4\u20138\n  |doi=\n  |accessdate=3 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"vicki\">{{cite news \n  |author=Dampier, Bill\n  |title=Broadview-Greenwood: Inflation, jobs major worries for residents\n  |url=\n  |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]\n  |location=\n  |date=25 January 1980\n  |page=A13\n  |accessdate=\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"EC\">{{\n  |title=1980 Election Results\n  |author=[[Elections Canada]]\n  |url=http://data2.collectionscanada.ca/open-data_donnees-ouvertes/G0000811_1.txt\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Canadian federal election, 1980A}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rhinoceros Party Candidates, 1980 Canadian Federal Election}}\n[[Category:Rhinoceros Party of Canada candidates in the 1980 Canadian federal election| ]]\n\n\n{{Canada-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Double pipe in a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhinoceros_Party_of_Canada_candidates_in_the_1980_Canadian_federal_election"}
{"title_page": "Snake Pass", "text_new": "{{about||the novel by Bram Stoker|The Snake's Pass|the 2017 video game | Snake Pass (video game)}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox mountain pass\n| name = Snake Pass\n| photo = Snake Pass - geograph.org.uk - 431557.jpg\n| photo_caption = Approaching the summit<br>from the Snake Pass Inn\n| elevation = {{convert|1680|ft|m}}\n| traversed = [[A57 road|A57]]\n| range = [[Pennines]]\n| map = Derbyshire\n| map_caption = Location within the [[Peak District]] in [[Derbyshire]]\n| map_size = 180\n| location = [[High Peak Estate]], [[Peak District]], [[Derbyshire]], [[England]]\n| coords = {{coord|53.4329|N|1.8689|W|type:pass_region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Snake Pass''' is a [[mountain pass|hill pass]] in the [[Derbyshire]] section of the [[Peak District]], crossing the [[Pennines]] between [[Glossop]] and the [[Ladybower Reservoir]] at [[Ashopton]]. The road was engineered by [[Thomas Telford]] and opened in 1821. The pass carries the [[A57 road]] between [[Manchester]] and [[Sheffield]], but it is no longer the main signposted route between those two cities.\n\nLike several other roads that cross the Pennines, Snake Pass has a poor [[Traffic collision|accident]] record compared with roads in the UK generally, although more favourable compared with other roads in the area. It is regularly closed in winter because of snow, and has seen several longer-term closures owing to [[subsidence]] following heavy rain. The road remains a popular route for tourists and motorcycles, however, and sections have been used for semi-professional cycling races such as the [[Tour of Britain]].\n\n==Route and location==\n[[File:Pennine Way at A57 Snake Pass summit - geograph.org.uk - 22692.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Pennine Way]] crosses Snake Pass at its summit.]]\nSnake Pass runs through the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]'s [[High Peak Estate]], and lies within the [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]] borough of [[Derbyshire]]; much of it falls within the [[Hope Woodlands]] parish, the remainder being within the [[Charlesworth, Derbyshire|Charlesworth]] parish.<ref name=map/><ref name=cox>{{cite book|title=English inn and tavern names|first=Barrie|last=Cox|publisher=English Place Name Society|year=1994|p=36|isbn=978-0-904889-42-0}}</ref> It is part of the shortest route by road from [[Manchester]] to [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Failures in earthworks: proceedings of the Symposium on Failures in Earthworks|editor=Institution of Civil Engineers|publisher=Thomas Telford|p=29|year=1985|isbn=978-0-7277-0243-2}}</ref>\n\nThe pass starts east of [[Glossop]] and climbs to the [[Pennines]] [[drainage divide|watershed]] between the moorland plateaux of [[Kinder Scout]] and [[Bleaklow]] to a high point of {{convert|1680|ft|m}} above sea level, where it crosses the [[Pennine Way]]. After this, it passes a [[public house]] that used to be known as the Snake Inn, and descends through forest to the [[Ladybower Reservoir]] at [[Ashopton]].<ref name=map>{{cite map|title=The Peak District \u2013 Dark Peak Area|publisher=Ordnance Survey|id=OL 1|scale=1:25 000|year=2010}}</ref>\n\nThe name of the road matches its winding route, but actually derives from the emblem of the Snake Inn, one of the few buildings on the high stretch of road. In turn, the pub's name and sign were derived from the serpent on the Cavendish arms of [[William Cavendish, 6th Duke of Devonshire]].<ref name=dillon/> In the early 21st century, the inn was renamed the Snake Pass Inn, such that the inn now refers to the road that referred to itself.<ref name=dillon>{{cite book|title=The Pennine Way|first=Paddy|last=Dillon|p=40|publisher=Cicerone Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-84965-359-6|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EEbEmUkVf8wC&pg=PA40}}</ref><ref name=turner/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Snake Pass Inn - geograph.org.uk - 5577.jpg|thumb|The Snake Pass Inn was originally called the Snake Inn, but is now named after the pass itself, which in turn was named after the pub.]]\nThe first road between Glossop and Ashopton was the Doctor's Gate, a [[Roman Road]] that follows the Shelf Brook between Shelf Moor and Coldharbour Moor, a route popular today with walkers and [[mountain bike racing|mountain bikers]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Hidden Places of England|publisher=Travel|p=478|year=2000|isbn=978-1-902007-43-4}}</ref> In 1932, an [[Iron Age]] axe thought to be more than 2,000 years old was found near the site of this road.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000541/19321105/225/0010|title=Perfectly Shaped Axe Found near Shopton|newspaper=Derbyshire Times and Chesterfield Herald|date=5 November 1932|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe current road further south was designed as a [[toll roads in Great Britain|toll road]] by [[Thomas Telford]] to improve communications east of Glossop, which was expanding as an industrial town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/rd/6497500e-f647-4d1c-8811-03689b770720|title=John Overend Todd Archive: Howard of Glossop Estate|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> It was originally called the Sheffield to Glossop Turnpike and run by a [[turnpike trust]], the Sheffield and Glossop Trust. An [[act of parliament]] to build the road was passed in 1818, and construction was financed by the [[Bernard Howard, 12th Duke of Norfolk|Duke of Norfolk]] and the Duke of Devonshire.<ref name=albert>{{cite book|title=The Turnpike Road System in England: 1663\u20131840|first=William|last=Albert|p=105|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-521-03391-6}}</ref> The road opened in 1821,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://list.historicengland.org.uk/resultsingle_print.aspx?uid=1203888&showMap=1&showText=1|title=SK 19 SW Parish of Hope Woodlands Snake Road 11/19 (South Side) Milestone II|publisher=historicengland.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> having cost \u00a318,625 to build.<ref name=albert/> Upon opening, it was the highest turnpike road in England.<ref name=ddt>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000327/19241101/007/0003|newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph|p=3|title=Town and County Gossip|date=1 November 1924|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The road was immediately popular and increased toll collections of traffic heading to Glossop.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000491/18220504/028/0003|title=Turpike Tolls to let|newspaper=Sheffield Independent|p=3|date=4 May 1822|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Tolls were abolished on the road in June 1870.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000181/18830508/006/0002|title=Local Turnpikes Case|newspaper=Sheffield Independent|p=2|date=8 May 1883|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe eastern end of the pass is by the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]]. The river is bridged by the Ashopton Viaduct, built as part of the [[Ladybower Reservoir]] project between 1935 and 1945.<ref>{{cite news|title=Full Description of the Ladybower Reservoir|newspaper=Derbyshire Times and Chesterfield Herald|p=7|date=21 September 1945|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Snake Pass is still the shortest route between Manchester and Sheffield, the more northerly [[Longdendale|Woodhead Pass]], which is less steep and at a lower altitude, is now the primary road link between the two cities. Unlike Snake Pass, the Woodhead route is a [[trunk road]]. Traffic levels on both passes remained similar until the 1980s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1984/mar/19/woodhead-route|title=Woodhead Route|work=Hansard|date=19 March 1984|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> but the Woodhead Pass route is now favoured as it connects directly to the [[M1 motorway (England)|M1]], while Snake Pass leads into the centre of Sheffield. Despite Sheffield and Manchester being among the [[List of cities in the United Kingdom|largest UK cities by population]],<ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/321814/14-802-people-in-cities-numbers.pdf|title=People in cities: the numbers|first=Tony|last=Champion|publisher=Government Office for Science|p=53|date=June 2014|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> there is no direct motorway link between the two. A Manchester to Sheffield motorway was first proposed in 1966,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1967/mar/01/sheffield-manchester-motorway|title=Sheffield \u2013 Manchester motorway|first=Barbara|last=Castle|authorlink=Barbara Castle|work=Hansard|date=1 March 1967|accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> and a small section bypassing [[Denton, Greater Manchester|Denton]] and [[Hyde, Greater Manchester|Hyde]] has been built, now the [[M67 motorway|M67]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://motorwayarchive.ihtservices.co.uk/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m67-hyde-bypass-and-denton-relief-road/|title=M67 Hyde By-pass and Denton Relief Road|publisher=The Motorway Archive|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref> The [[Woodhead Tunnel]] was closed in 1981 in anticipation of a road replacement, but linking the cities would have meant constructing many costly tunnels and viaducts across the Peak District. Consequently, the plans were shelved, but reports in December 2014 announced a revival of the scheme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-30277068|title=Sheffield to Manchester \u00a36bn road tunnel 'plan' announced|work=BBC News|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe road remains popular with drivers. In 2008, a survey by [[Caterham Cars]] rated Snake Pass the best driving road in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/what-s-on/out-about/snake-pass-is-voted-best-road-1-254557|title=Snake Pass is voted best road|work=The Star|location=Sheffield|date=16 September 2008|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The following year, it was listed as one of the best roads for driving in Britain by ''[[Auto Trader Group|Auto Trader]]'' magazine, who described it as \"offering unparalleled views over Manchester\".<ref>{{cite news |title=England's best driving road \u2013 revealed |url=http://www.autotrader.co.uk/EDITORIAL/car_page_content/englands_best_driving_road_revealed.html |work=Auto Trader Magazine |date=23 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312152642/http://www.autotrader.co.uk/EDITORIAL/car_page_content/englands_best_driving_road_revealed.html| archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n[[File:A57 - A dangerous road - geograph.org.uk - 616076.jpg|thumb|An abandoned car left hanging off the edge of Snake Pass, 1983]]\nAs would be expected for a road crossing the Pennines, Snake Pass has several dangerous bends and blind summits.<ref name=turner>{{cite book|title=Bonjour \u2013 Is This Italy?: A Hapless Biker's Guide to Europe|p=18|first=Kevin|last=Turner|publisher=Veloce Publishing Ltd|year=2012|isbn=978-1-84584-399-1}}</ref> Like many roads in the [[North of England]] passing through similar terrain, Snake Pass has a poor safety record in comparison to other roads in the United Kingdom but it is not as dangerous as other roads bisecting hilly terrain in this part of England. It was not among the top 10 in a list of the most dangerous roads published in July 2010, despite nine of the top ten being in Northern England.<ref>{{Cite news |title='Most dangerous' roads in Britain named by safety group |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10454356 |publisher=BBC News |date=1 July 2010 |accessdate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Derbyshire Police announced a campaign to monitor motorcyclists using the pass, who are particularly at risk of being involved in a fatal accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/police-in-bid-to-reduce-snake-pass-686095|title=Police in bid to reduce Snake Pass road deaths|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=5 April 2012|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Weather==\n[[File:Snake Pass retaining wall repairs.JPG|thumb|left|Repair work to one of the highway's retaining walls, June 2015]]\nIn winter the road is often the first of the routes between Sheffield and Manchester to be closed following snow in the area.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mountains of England and Wales|first=Anne|last=Nuttall|p=293|publisher=Cicerone Press Limited|year=1990|isbn=978-1-85284-037-2}}</ref> In bad storms the entire road over the summit, including marker poles, has been buried in snow.<ref name=ddt/> In the winter months the road becomes icy, but gritting is not a priority as the A57 is only a \"secondary\" road at this point.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sheffieldinnews.com/update-snake-pass-closed-again-because-of-abandoned-cars-2/|title=Snake Pass closed again because of abandoned cars|newspaper=Sheffield Telegraph|date=18 January 2015|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> Local councils prefer to treat streets in towns that are more likely to be used, as they believe that roads such as Snake Pass will be closed anyway.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.highpeak.gov.uk/sites/default/files/meetings/papers/HPBC_04_Environment_Select_Committee_20100309.pdf|title=Environment Select Committee Meeting|publisher=High Peak Borough Council|date=16 February 2010|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924 Derbyshire County Council spent \u00a32,000 installing underground telegraph wire cables beneath the road, as the above-ground installations were continually broken and disrupted following snowstorms.<ref name=ddt/> The [[Winter of 2010\u201311 in Great Britain and Ireland|British winter of 2010\u201311]] was the coldest for decades and the road was closed on numerous occasions.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Derbyshire hit by road and school closures over snow |quote=The A57 Snake Pass is closed in both directions between the Hurst Road junction in Glossop and the A6013. |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-11901184 |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Snake Pass closed as snow returns |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/snake-pass-closed-as-snow-returns-1220905|first=Sue|last=Carr|newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=17 December 2010 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nSnake Pass has also been closed for longer periods owing to [[subsidence]] in the local area following rain. In January 1932 the road was closed after 200 tonnes of debris fell on it during a heavy rainstorm, covering the surface in as much as {{convert|4|ft|m}} in places.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landslide on the Snake|newspaper=Derbyshire Times and Chesterfield Herald|p=12|date=9 January 1932|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref> In January 2008 a landslip at Cowms Moor following heavy rain caused the road to be closed to all traffic between Ladybower and Glossop, although access was still available to local premises and businesses including the Snake Pass Inn.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/what-s-on/traffic-alert-landslide-closes-a57-1-235050|title=TRAFFIC ALERT: Landslide closes A57|newspaper=Sheffield Telegraph|date=25 January 2008|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=nerc>{{cite report|url=http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/3724/1/OR08006.pdf|title=Walkover survey of a landslide on the A57 (Snake Pass) road at Cowms Moor, Derbyshire in January 2008|publisher=British Geographical Survey|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> A subsequent investigation by the British Geographical Survey showed the road has had a history of subsidence-related long-term closures dating back to the 1930s, including a 1970s project that attempted to strengthen the layer below the tarmac with local rock fill. The road reopened in February, but with temporary traffic lights at the point of the slip restricting traffic to one direction at a time.<ref name=nerc/> In 2012 the road had to be closed several times for resurfacing and strengthening.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/snake-pass-to-close-for-three-weekends-801116|title=Snake Pass to close for three weekends|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=29 October 2012|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Cycling==\nSnake Pass is a popular route for cyclists. A 1902 report on leisure cycling in the ''Lancashire Evening Post'' described the eastward journey from the summit to Ashopton as \"nine miles unbroken freewheeling\" and the scenery as \"magnificent\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000711/19021203/068/0004|title=Cycling Notes by Ixion|newspaper=Lancashire Evening Post|p=4|date=3 December 1902|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The road is one of only a few road climbs in the UK that are comparable in length and average gradient (approximately 7 per cent for around {{convert|3.2|mi|km}} when starting in [[Glossop]]) to those used in continental cycle racing.<ref name=jones>{{cite book|title=Mad Dogs and Englishmen: A Year of Things to See and Do in England|p=50|first=Tom|last=Jones|publisher=Random House|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7535-4957-5}}</ref> The road had been part of an 82-mile \"Tour of the Peak\" race, involving climbing the pass twice,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000379/19430618/019/0003|title=Cycling : Despatch from \"Clubman\"|newspaper=Lichfield Mercury|date=18 June 1943|p=3|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and has frequently featured in the [[Tour of Britain]] along with another nearby favourite, [[Holme Moss]].<ref name=jones/>\n\n[[Cycling Time Trials]] sanctioned hill climbs are regularly promoted on this course by local club Glossop Kinder Velo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glossopkindervelo.co.uk/index.php/cycling-events/snake-pass-hill-climb/|title=Snake Pass hill Climb|publisher=Glossop Kinder Velo|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The record for completing the course was set by Tejvan Pettinger in 2014, at 11 minutes 51 seconds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/british-racing/tejvan-pettinger-wins-glossop-kinder-velo-hill-climb-134358|title=Tejvan Pettinger wins Glossop Kinder Velo hill-climb|newspaper=Cycling Weekly|date=31 August 2014|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nSnake Pass has been referred to several times by music groups. The track \"The Snake\" by Sheffield band [[the Human League]], from their 2001 album ''[[Secrets (Human League album)|Secrets]]'', is about the road.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/places/taking_the_high_road_from_glossop_to_ladybower_1_1570809|title=Taking the High Road from Glossop to Ladybower|work=Derbyshire Life and Countryside|date=21 July 2012|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref> The [[Squarepusher]] album ''[[Selection Sixteen]]'' features a track entitled \"Snake Pass\", described by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as a \"monomaniacal thump\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|p=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/773 773]|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7432-0169-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/773}}</ref>\n\nComic character [[John Shuttleworth (character)|John Shuttleworth]] has performed a song called \"Incident on Snake Pass\" about the perils of Snake Pass, relating to an accident he claimed to have had, driving a [[Ford Anglia]] on the road.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thevisitor.co.uk/news/shuttleworth-s-on-a-roll-1-2227188|title=Shuttleworth's on a roll|newspaper=The Visitor|date=20 October 2010|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/kinder-edale-and-the-dark-peak National Trust description of the area]\n\n{{good article}}\n{{High Peak}}\n\n[[Category:Mountain passes of England]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n[[Category:Scenic routes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Transport in Derbyshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the novel by Bram Stoker|The Snake's Pass|the 2017 video game | Snake Pass (video game)}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox mountain pass\n| name = Snake Pass\n| photo = Snake Pass - geograph.org.uk - 431557.jpg\n| photo_caption = Approaching the summit<br>from the Snake Pass Inn\n| elevation = {{convert|1680|ft|m}}\n| traversed = [[A57 road|A57]]\n| range = [[Pennines]]\n| map = Derbyshire\n| map_caption = Location within the [[Peak District]] in [[Derbyshire]]\n| map_size = 180\n| location = [[High Peak Estate]], [[Peak District]], [[Derbyshire]], [[England]]\n| coords = {{coord|53.4329|N|1.8689|W|type:pass_region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Snake Pass''' is a [[mountain pass|hill pass]] in the [[Derbyshire]] section of the [[Peak District]], crossing the [[Pennines]] between [[Glossop]] and the [[Ladybower Reservoir]] at [[Ashopton]]. The road was engineered by [[Thomas Telford]] and opened in 1821. The pass carries the [[A57 road]] between [[Manchester]] and [[Sheffield]], but it is no longer the main signposted route between those two cities.\n\nLike several other roads that cross the Pennines, Snake Pass has a poor [[Traffic collision|accident]] record compared with roads in the UK generally, although more favourable compared with other roads in the area. It is regularly closed in winter because of snow, and has seen several longer-term closures owing to [[subsidence]] following heavy rain. The road remains a popular route for tourists and motorcycles, however, and sections have been used for semi-professional cycling races such as the [[Tour of Britain]].\n\n==Route and location==\n[[File:Pennine Way at A57 Snake Pass summit - geograph.org.uk - 22692.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Pennine Way]] crosses Snake Pass at its summit.]]\nSnake Pass runs through the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]'s [[High Peak Estate]], and lies within the [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]] borough of [[Derbyshire]]; much of it falls within the [[Hope Woodlands]] parish, the remainder being within the [[Charlesworth, Derbyshire|Charlesworth]] parish.<ref name=map/><ref name=cox>{{cite book|title=English inn and tavern names|first=Barrie|last=Cox|publisher=English Place Name Society|year=1994|p=36|isbn=978-0-904889-42-0}}</ref> It is part of the shortest route by road from [[Manchester]] to [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Failures in earthworks: proceedings of the Symposium on Failures in Earthworks|editor=Institution of Civil Engineers|publisher=Thomas Telford|p=29|year=1985|isbn=978-0-7277-0243-2}}</ref>\n\nThe pass starts east of [[Glossop]] and climbs to the [[Pennines]] [[drainage divide|watershed]] between the moorland plateaux of [[Kinder Scout]] and [[Bleaklow]] to a high point of {{convert|1680|ft|m}} above sea level, where it crosses the [[Pennine Way]]. After this, it passes a [[public house]] that used to be known as the Snake Inn, and descends through forest to the [[Ladybower Reservoir]] at [[Ashopton]].<ref name=map>{{cite map|title=The Peak District \u2013 Dark Peak Area|publisher=Ordnance Survey|id=OL 1|scale=1:25 000|year=2010}}</ref>\n\nThe name of the road matches its winding route, but actually derives from the emblem of the Snake Inn, one of the few buildings on the high stretch of road. In turn, the pub's name and sign were derived from the serpent on the Cavendish arms of [[William Cavendish, 6th Duke of Devonshire]].<ref name=dillon/> In the early 21st century, the inn was renamed the Snake Pass Inn, such that the inn now refers to the road that referred to itself.<ref name=dillon>{{cite book|title=The Pennine Way|first=Paddy|last=Dillon|p=40|publisher=Cicerone Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-84965-359-6|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EEbEmUkVf8wC&pg=PA40}}</ref><ref name=turner/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Snake Pass Inn - geograph.org.uk - 5577.jpg|thumb|The Snake Pass Inn was originally called the Snake Inn, but is now named after the pass itself, which in turn was named after the pub.]]\nThe first road between Glossop and Ashopton was the Doctor's Gate, a [[Roman Road]] that follows the Shelf Brook between Shelf Moor and Coldharbour Moor, a route popular today with walkers and [[mountain bike racing|mountain bikers]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Hidden Places of England|publisher=Travel|p=478|year=2000|isbn=978-1-902007-43-4}}</ref> In 1932, an [[Iron Age]] axe thought to be more than 2,000 years old was found near the site of this road.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000541/19321105/225/0010|title=Perfectly Shaped Axe Found near Shopton|newspaper=Derbyshire Times and Chesterfield Herald|date=5 November 1932|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe current road further south was designed as a [[toll roads in Great Britain|toll road]] by [[Thomas Telford]] to improve communications east of Glossop, which was expanding as an industrial town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/rd/6497500e-f647-4d1c-8811-03689b770720|title=John Overend Todd Archive: Howard of Glossop Estate|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> It was originally called the Sheffield to Glossop Turnpike and run by a [[turnpike trust]], the Sheffield and Glossop Trust. An [[act of parliament]] to build the road was passed in 1818, and construction was financed by the [[Bernard Howard, 12th Duke of Norfolk|Duke of Norfolk]] and the Duke of Devonshire.<ref name=albert>{{cite book|title=The Turnpike Road System in England: 1663\u20131840|first=William|last=Albert|p=105|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0-521-03391-6}}</ref> The road opened in 1821,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://list.historicengland.org.uk/resultsingle_print.aspx?uid=1203888&showMap=1&showText=1|title=SK 19 SW Parish of Hope Woodlands Snake Road 11/19 (South Side) Milestone II|publisher=historicengland.org.uk|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> having cost \u00a318,625 to build.<ref name=albert/> Upon opening, it was the highest turnpike road in England.<ref name=ddt>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000327/19241101/007/0003|newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph|p=3|title=Town and County Gossip|date=1 November 1924|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The road was immediately popular and increased toll collections of traffic heading to Glossop.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000491/18220504/028/0003|title=Turpike Tolls to let|newspaper=Sheffield Independent|p=3|date=4 May 1822|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Tolls were abolished on the road in June 1870.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000181/18830508/006/0002|title=Local Turnpikes Case|newspaper=Sheffield Independent|p=2|date=8 May 1883|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThe eastern end of the pass is by the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]]. The river is bridged by the Ashopton Viaduct, built as part of the [[Ladybower Reservoir]] project between 1935 and 1945.<ref>{{cite news|title=Full Description of the Ladybower Reservoir|newspaper=Derbyshire Times and Chesterfield Herald|p=7|date=21 September 1945|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Snake Pass is still the shortest route between Manchester and Sheffield, the more northerly [[Longdendale|Woodhead Pass]], which is less steep and at a lower altitude, is now the primary road link between the two cities. Unlike Snake Pass, the Woodhead route is a [[trunk road]]. Traffic levels on both passes remained similar until the 1980s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1984/mar/19/woodhead-route|title=Woodhead Route|work=Hansard|date=19 March 1984|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> but the Woodhead Pass route is now favoured as it connects directly to the [[M1 motorway (England)|M1]], while Snake Pass leads into the centre of Sheffield. Despite Sheffield and Manchester being among the [[List of cities in the United Kingdom|largest UK cities by population]],<ref>{{cite report|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/321814/14-802-people-in-cities-numbers.pdf|title=People in cities: the numbers|first=Tony|last=Champion|publisher=Government Office for Science|p=53|date=June 2014|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> there is no direct motorway link between the two. A Manchester to Sheffield motorway was first proposed in 1966,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1967/mar/01/sheffield-manchester-motorway|title=Sheffield \u2013 Manchester motorway|first=Barbara|last=Castle|authorlink=Barbara Castle|work=Hansard|date=1 March 1967|accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> and a small section bypassing [[Denton, Greater Manchester|Denton]] and [[Hyde, Greater Manchester|Hyde]] has been built, now the [[M67 motorway|M67]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://motorwayarchive.ihtservices.co.uk/en/motorways/motorway-listing/m67-hyde-bypass-and-denton-relief-road/|title=M67 Hyde By-pass and Denton Relief Road|publisher=The Motorway Archive|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref> The [[Woodhead Tunnel]] was closed in 1981 in anticipation of a road replacement, but linking the cities would have meant constructing many costly tunnels and viaducts across the Peak District. Consequently, the plans were shelved, but reports in December 2014 announced a revival of the scheme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-30277068|title=Sheffield to Manchester \u00a36bn road tunnel 'plan' announced|work=BBC News|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe road remains popular with drivers. In 2008, a survey by [[Caterham Cars]] rated Snake Pass the best driving road in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/what-s-on/out-about/snake-pass-is-voted-best-road-1-254557|title=Snake Pass is voted best road|work=The Star|location=Sheffield|date=16 September 2008|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The following year, it was listed as one of the best roads for driving in Britain by ''[[Auto Trader Group|Auto Trader]]'' magazine, who described it as \"offering unparalleled views over Manchester\".<ref>{{cite news |title=England's best driving road \u2013 revealed |url=http://www.autotrader.co.uk/EDITORIAL/car_page_content/englands_best_driving_road_revealed.html |work=Auto Trader Magazine |date=23 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312152642/http://www.autotrader.co.uk/EDITORIAL/car_page_content/englands_best_driving_road_revealed.html| archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n[[File:A57 - A dangerous road - geograph.org.uk - 616076.jpg|thumb|An abandoned car left hanging off the edge of Snake Pass, 1983]]\nAs would be expected for a road crossing the Pennines, Snake Pass has several dangerous bends and blind summits.<ref name=turner>{{cite book|title=Bonjour \u2013 Is This Italy?: A Hapless Biker's Guide to Europe|p=18|first=Kevin|last=Turner|publisher=Veloce Publishing Ltd|year=2012|isbn=978-1-84584-399-1}}</ref> Like many roads in the [[North of England]] passing through similar terrain, Snake Pass has a poor safety record in comparison to other roads in the United Kingdom but it is not as dangerous as other roads bisecting hilly terrain in this part of England. It was not among the top 10 in a list of the most dangerous roads published in July 2010, despite nine of the top ten being in Northern England.<ref>{{Cite news |title='Most dangerous' roads in Britain named by safety group |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10454356 |publisher=BBC News |date=1 July 2010 |accessdate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Derbyshire Police announced a campaign to monitor motorcyclists using the pass, who are particularly at risk of being involved in a fatal accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/police-in-bid-to-reduce-snake-pass-686095|title=Police in bid to reduce Snake Pass road deaths|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=5 April 2012|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Weather==\n[[File:Snake Pass retaining wall repairs.JPG|thumb|left|Repair work to one of the highway's retaining walls, June 2015]]\nIn winter the road is often the first of the routes between Sheffield and Manchester to be closed following snow in the area.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mountains of England and Wales|first=Anne|last=Nuttall|p=293|publisher=Cicerone Press Limited|year=1990|isbn=978-1-85284-037-2}}</ref> In bad storms the entire road over the summit, including marker poles, has been buried in snow.<ref name=ddt/> In the winter months the road becomes icy, but gritting is not a priority as the A57 is only a \"secondary\" road at this point.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sheffieldinnews.com/update-snake-pass-closed-again-because-of-abandoned-cars-2/|title=Snake Pass closed again because of abandoned cars|newspaper=Sheffield Telegraph|date=18 January 2015|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> Local councils prefer to treat streets in towns that are more likely to be used, as they believe that roads such as Snake Pass will be closed anyway.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.highpeak.gov.uk/sites/default/files/meetings/papers/HPBC_04_Environment_Select_Committee_20100309.pdf|title=Environment Select Committee Meeting|publisher=High Peak Borough Council|date=16 February 2010|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924 Derbyshire County Council spent \u00a32,000 installing underground telegraph wire cables beneath the road, as the above-ground installations were continually broken and disrupted following snowstorms.<ref name=ddt/> The [[Winter of 2010\u201311 in Great Britain and Ireland|British winter of 2010\u201311]] was the coldest for decades and the road was closed on numerous occasions.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Derbyshire hit by road and school closures over snow |quote=The A57 Snake Pass is closed in both directions between the Hurst Road junction in Glossop and the A6013. |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-11901184 |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Snake Pass closed as snow returns |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/snake-pass-closed-as-snow-returns-1220905|first=Sue|last=Carr|newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=17 December 2010 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nSnake Pass has also been closed for longer periods owing to [[subsidence]] in the local area following rain. In January 1932 the road was closed after 200 tonnes of debris fell on it during a heavy rainstorm, covering the surface in as much as {{convert|4|ft|m}} in places.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landslide on the Snake|newspaper=Derbyshire Times and Chesterfield Herald|p=12|date=9 January 1932|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref> In January 2008 a landslip at Cowms Moor following heavy rain caused the road to be closed to all traffic between Ladybower and Glossop, although access was still available to local premises and businesses including the Snake Pass Inn.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/what-s-on/traffic-alert-landslide-closes-a57-1-235050|title=TRAFFIC ALERT: Landslide closes A57|newspaper=Sheffield Telegraph|date=25 January 2008|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=nerc>{{cite report|url=http://nora.nerc.ac.uk/3724/1/OR08006.pdf|title=Walkover survey of a landslide on the A57 (Snake Pass) road at Cowms Moor, Derbyshire in January 2008|publisher=British Geographical Survey|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> A subsequent investigation by the British Geographical Survey showed the road has had a history of subsidence-related long-term closures dating back to the 1930s, including a 1970s project that attempted to strengthen the layer below the tarmac with local rock fill. The road reopened in February, but with temporary traffic lights at the point of the slip restricting traffic to one direction at a time.<ref name=nerc/> In 2012 the road had to be closed several times for resurfacing and strengthening.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/snake-pass-to-close-for-three-weekends-801116|title=Snake Pass to close for three weekends|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|date=29 October 2012|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Cycling==\nSnake Pass is a popular route for cyclists. A 1902 report on leisure cycling in the ''Lancashire Evening Post'' described the eastward journey from the summit to Ashopton as \"nine miles unbroken freewheeling\" and the scenery as \"magnificent\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000711/19021203/068/0004|title=Cycling Notes by Ixion|newspaper=Lancashire Evening Post|p=4|date=3 December 1902|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The road is one of only a few road climbs in the UK that are comparable in length and average gradient (approximately 7 per cent for around {{convert|3.2|mi|km}} when starting in [[Glossop]]) to those used in continental cycle racing.<ref name=jones>{{cite book|title=Mad Dogs and Englishmen: A Year of Things to See and Do in England|p=50|first=Tom|last=Jones|publisher=Random House|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7535-4957-5}}</ref> The road had been part of an 82-mile \"Tour of the Peak\" race, involving climbing the pass twice,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000379/19430618/019/0003|title=Cycling : Despatch from \"Clubman\"|newspaper=Lichfield Mercury|date=18 June 1943|p=3|accessdate=27 March 2015|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and has frequently featured in the [[Tour of Britain]] along with another nearby favourite, [[Holme Moss]].<ref name=jones/>\n\n[[Cycling Time Trials]] sanctioned hill climbs are regularly promoted on this course by local club Glossop Kinder Velo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glossopkindervelo.co.uk/index.php/cycling-events/snake-pass-hill-climb/|title=Snake Pass hill Climb|publisher=Glossop Kinder Velo|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The record for completing the course was set by Tejvan Pettinger in 2014, at 11 minutes 51 seconds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/british-racing/tejvan-pettinger-wins-glossop-kinder-velo-hill-climb-134358|title=Tejvan Pettinger wins Glossop Kinder Velo hill-climb|newspaper=Cycling Weekly|date=31 August 2014|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nSnake Pass has been referred to several times by music groups. The track \"The Snake\" by Sheffield band [[the Human League]], from their 2001 album ''[[Secrets (Human League album)|Secrets]]'', is about the road.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.derbyshirelife.co.uk/out-about/places/taking_the_high_road_from_glossop_to_ladybower_1_1570809|title=Taking the High Road from Glossop to Ladybower|work=Derbyshire Life and Countryside|date=21 July 2012|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref> The [[Squarepusher]] album ''[[Selection Sixteen]]'' features a track entitled \"Snake Pass\", described by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' as a \"monomaniacal thump\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|p=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/773 773]|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7432-0169-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/773}}</ref>\n\nComic character [[John Shuttleworth (character)|John Shuttleworth]] has performed a song called \"Incident on Snake Pass\" about the perils of Snake Pass, relating to an accident he claimed to have had, driving a [[Ford Anglia]] on the road.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thevisitor.co.uk/news/shuttleworth-s-on-a-roll-1-2227188|title=Shuttleworth's on a roll|newspaper=The Visitor|date=20 October 2010|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/kinder-edale-and-the-dark-peak National Trust description of the area]\n\n{{good article}}\n{{High Peak}}\n\n[[Category:Mountain passes of England]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n[[Category:Scenic routes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Transport in Derbyshire]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak, Derbyshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snake_Pass"}
{"title_page": "Jack Swigert", "text_new": "{{use mdy|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Jack Swigert\n| birth_name    = John Leonard Swigert Jr.\n| image         = Jack Swigert- Apollo 13.jpg\n| image_size    = 230\n| caption       = Swigert in April 1970\n| office        = Member-elect of the <br /> [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] <br /> from [[Colorado]]'s [[Colorado's 6th congressional district|6th]] district\n| term         = '''''Died before taking office'''''\n| predecessor   = ''Constituency established''\n| successor     = [[Daniel Schaefer]] \n| nationality   = American\n| birth_date    = August 30, 1931\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1982|12|27|1931|8|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Denver]], Colorado, U.S.\n| death_place   = [[Washington D.C.]], U.S.\n| restingplace  = [[Mount Olivet Cemetery (Wheat Ridge)|Mount Olivet Cemetery]],<br />[[Wheat Ridge, Colorado]]\n| alma_mater    = {{unbulleted list|[[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]],<br />B.S. 1953|[[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], M.S. 1965|[[University of Hartford]],<br />MBA 1967}}\n| occupation    = [[Fighter pilot]], [[test pilot]], [[astronaut]]\n| party         = [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] \n|allegiance   = {{USA}}\n|branch       = [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] (1953\u20131956)\n|serviceyears = 1953\u20131965\n|rank         = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|25px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n|unit         = {{unbulleted list\n|[[Massachusetts Air National Guard]] (1957\u20131960)\n|[[Connecticut Air National Guard]] (1960\u20131965) \n}}\n|parents      = John L. Swigert, M.D.<br />Virginia Swigert\n| module = {{Infobox astronaut | child=yes\n   | image         = Jack Swigert.jpg\n   | type          = [[NASA]] astronaut\n   | selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 5|1966 NASA Group 5]]\n   | time          = 5d 22h 54m\n   | mission       = [[Apollo 13]]\n   | insignia      = [[Image:Apollo 13-insignia.png|45px]]\n   | Date of ret   = August 1977\n   | awards        = {{Presidential Medal of Freedom}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n   }}\n}}\n'''John Leonard Swigert Jr.''' (August 30, 1931 \u2013 December 27, 1982) was an American [[test pilot]], [[Mechanical engineering|mechanical]], [[aerospace engineer]], [[United States Air Force]] pilot, [[NASA]] [[astronaut]], and [[politician]]. In April 1970, as command module pilot of [[Apollo 13]], he became one of [[List of Apollo astronauts#Apollo astronauts who flew to the Moon without landing|twenty-four astronauts who flew to the Moon]].<ref name=exaschl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CVkvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9toFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1306%2C4053722 |newspaper=Beaver County Times |title=Ex-astronaut's challenge |last=Eicher |first=Diane |date=December 19, 1982 |page=B2|via=Google News}}</ref><ref name=nytobit>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/29/obituaries/jack-swigert-astronaut-elected-to-congress-dies.html |newspaper=The New York Times |title=Jack Swigert, astronaut elected to Congress, dies |last=Treaster |first=Joseph B. |date=December 29, 1982 |access-date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore joining NASA in 1966, Swigert was a civilian [[test pilot]] and [[fighter pilot]] in the [[Air National Guard]]. After leaving NASA, he lost a primary election against [[William L. Armstrong|Bill Armstrong]]. While running for [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]], he was diagnosed with cancer. He won the election for Colorado's new [[Colorado's 6th congressional district|6th district]], but died before being sworn in.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Leonard Swigert Jr. was born on August 30, 1931 in [[Denver]], Colorado to parents John Leonard Sr. (1903\u20131973) and Virginia Swigert (1906\u20131993). Swigert's father was an [[Ophthalmology|ophthalmologist]].<ref name=exaschl/><ref name=nytobit/> At the age of 14, he became fascinated by aviation. While he would have been content just watching planes take off from nearby Combs Field, young Jack became determined to do more than be a spectator. He took on a newspaper route to earn money for flying lessons, and by age 16 he was a [[Private pilot licence|licensed private pilot]].<ref name=\"americaspace\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americaspace.com/?p=66745|title=For Jack Swigert, On His 83rd Birthday|last1=Carney|first1=Emily|publisher=AmericaSpace|access-date=November 27, 2017|date=April 29, 2014}}</ref> He attended [[Blessed Sacrament School (Denver, Colorado)|Blessed Sacrament School]], [[Regis Jesuit High School]], and [[East High School (Denver)|East High School]], from which he graduated in 1949.<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html|title=John L. Swigert Jr., NASA Astronaut (Deceased)|publisher=NASA JSC|access-date=November 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143646/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html|archive-date=April 20, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSwigert received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[mechanical engineering]] from the [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] in 1953, where he also played [[American football|football]] for the [[Colorado Buffaloes football|Buffaloes]].<ref name=exaschl/><ref name=nytobit/> He later earned a [[Master of Science]] degree in [[aerospace engineering]] from the [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] (Hartford campus) in 1965,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43310515/hartford_courant/|title=Astronaut is Honored by Chamber, School|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=April 29, 1966|page=21|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[University of Hartford]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43311499/hartford_courant/|title=Astronaut Receives Degree|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=June 11, 1967|page=42|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nHis recreational interests included [[golf]], [[American handball|handball]], [[bowling]], [[skiing]], [[Human swimming|swimming]], and [[basketball]]. His hobbies included [[photography]].<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" />\n\nHe was a member of the [[Boy Scouts of America]] and attained the rank of [[Second Class (Boy Scouts of America)|Second Class Scout]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx|title=Scouting and Space Exploration|website=Boy Scouts of America|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000000/http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx |archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usscouts.org/eagle/eagleastronauts.asp |title=Astronauts with Scouting experience|publisher= US Scouting Service|date=August 26, 2012|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Flight experience==\n[[File:Apollo13 apparatus.jpg|thumb|left|Swigert, at right, with the \"mailbox\" rig improvised to adapt the Apollo 13 [[Apollo command module|command module]]'s square [[carbon dioxide]] scrubber cartridges to fit the [[lunar module]], which took a round cartridge]]\n\nFollowing his graduation from Colorado in 1953, Swigert joined the [[U.S. Air Force]]. Upon graduation from the Pilot Training Program and [[USAF Weapons School#Origins|Gunnery School]] at [[Nellis Air Force Base]], [[Nevada]], he was assigned as a [[fighter pilot]] in Japan and Korea. In 1953, he survived his plane crashing into a radar unit on a Korean airstrip.<ref name=\"americaspace\" /><ref name=nytobit/>\n\nAfter completing his tour of active duty in the Air Force, he served as a jet fighter pilot with the [[Massachusetts Air National Guard|Massachusetts]] (1957\u20131960) and [[Connecticut Air National Guard]] (1960\u20131965).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43823204/abilene_reporternews/|title=Astronaut Swigert Began Flight Instruction at 14|newspaper=Abilene Reporter-News|location=Abilene, Texas|date=May 17, 1968|page=B-1|via=Newspapers.com|last1=Kershaw|first1=Tom}}</ref> Swigert held a position as engineering test pilot for [[North American Aviation]] before joining NASA. He was previously an engineering test pilot for [[Pratt & Whitney]], from February 1957 to June 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43822825/page_e1/|title=A Tribute: He 'Bore Holes in the Sky'|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=April 14, 1983|via=Newspapers.com|page=E1|last1=Pallatto|first1=John}}</ref>\n\nHe logged over 7,200 hours in flight, with more than 5,725 in [[jet aircraft]].<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\"/>\n\n==NASA career==\nAfter unsuccessfully applying for NASA's [[Astronaut Group 2|second]] and [[Astronaut Group 3|third]] astronaut selections,{{sfn|Chaikin|1998|p=307}} Swigert was accepted into the [[NASA Astronaut Corps]] as part of [[NASA Astronaut Group 5]] in April 1966.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28240973/the_high_point_enterprise/|title=19 New Spacemen Are Named|last1=Thompson|first1=Ronald|newspaper=The High Point Enterprise|location=High Point, North Carolina|date=April 5, 1966|page=2A|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Swigert became a specialist on the [[Apollo command module]]: he was one of the few astronauts who requested to be command module pilots.{{sfn|Chaikin|1998|p=307}}\n\nSwigert was a member of [[Apollo 7]]'s astronaut support crew, the first support crew for an Apollo mission.<ref name=atp>{{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/20319-jack-swigert-apollo-13-biography.html|title=Jack Swigert: Apollo 13 Astronaut Turned Politician|last1=Howell|first1=Elizabeth|date=March 20, 2013|access-date=January 28, 2020|website=Space.com}}</ref>\n\n===Apollo 13===\n{{Main|Apollo 13}}\nSwigert was one of three astronauts aboard the [[Apollo 13]] Moon mission launched April 11, 1970. Originally part of the backup crew for the mission, he was assigned to the mission three days before launch, replacing astronaut [[Ken Mattingly]]. The prime crew had been exposed to [[German Measles]] (the rubella virus) from [[Charles Duke]] and, because Mattingly had no immunity to the disease, NASA did not want to risk his falling ill during critical phases of the flight.{{sfn|Slayton|Cassutt|1994|p=256}}\n\nThe mission was the third crewed lunar-landing attempt, but was aborted after the rupture of an oxygen tank in the spacecraft's [[Apollo service module|service module]]. Swigert was the astronaut who made the dramatic announcement, \"[[Houston, we have a problem|Houston, we've had a problem here]]\".{{sfn|Lovell|1975}} The statement was then repeated by commander of the flight [[Jim Lovell]]. Swigert, along with fellow astronauts Lovell and [[Fred Haise]], traveled around the Moon and returned safely to Earth on April 17 after about 5 days and 23 hours, and received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=2472|title=Remarks on Presenting the Presidential Medal of Freedom to Apollo 13 Astronauts in Honolulu|publisher=The American Presidency Project|access-date=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Apollo\u2013Soyuz Test Project ===\nNASA Director of Flight Crew Operations [[Deke Slayton]], who selected the astronauts, recommended Swigert as [[command module pilot]] for the [[Apollo\u2013Soyuz Test Project]], the first joint mission with the Soviet Union. Slayton felt Swigert deserved another chance to fly after having been selected for Apollo 13 two days before launch, and performing well.{{sfn|Slayton|Cassutt|1994|p=278}}\n\nDuring 1972, the [[Apollo 15 postal covers incident]] caused NASA investigators to inquire into other astronauts.<ref name=\"americaspace\" /> A number of Apollo astronauts, including Swigert, had made agreements with West German stamp dealer Hermann Sieger, whose brainchild the [[Apollo 15]] covers was, to autograph philatelic items in exchange for a payment of about $2,500. Swigert originally denied involvement when interviewed by NASA investigators.{{sfn|Slayton|Cassutt|1994|p=279}} According to [[Christopher C. Kraft]], the investigators subpoenaed his bank records, finding more funds than expected, and records of a predated charitable donation.{{sfn|Kraft|p=344}} Swigert's subsequent admission caused NASA Deputy Administrator [[George M. Low]] to remove him from Apollo\u2013Soyuz.<ref name=\"americaspace\" />\n\n==Post-NASA career==\nAware that his spaceflight career was most likely over,<ref name=\"americaspace\" /> Swigert took a leave of absence from NASA in April 1973 to become executive director of the [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science and Astronautics]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"nmmuseum\" />\n\nSwigert eventually left NASA and the committee in August 1977 to enter politics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43299511/the_paducah_sun/|title=People...In the News|newspaper=The Paducah Sun|location=Paducah, Kentucky|date=September 27, 1977|page=3A|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He ran for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in 1978, but was soundly defeated in the Republican primary in September <!--12-->by [[Colorado's 5th congressional district|congressman]] [[William L. Armstrong|Bill Armstrong]].<ref name=pktmincm>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eiVVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-X8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5168%2C2943019 |work=Deseret News |location=Salt Lake City, Utah|agency=UPI |title=Primaries kind to most incumbents |date=September 13, 1978 |page=A-1|via=Google News}}</ref><!-- https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Results/Abstract/pdf/1900-1999/1978AbstractBook.pdf --> In 1979, Swigert became vice president of B.D.M. Corporation in [[Golden, Colorado|Golden]].<ref name=atp /> He left <!--BDM-->in 1981 to join International Gold and Minerals Limited as vice president for financial and corporate affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1982/12/29/rep-elect-swigert-dies/5f746229-6c2e-498b-a514-7ab426aef1ff/|title=Rep.-Elect Swigert Dies|last1=Ringle|first1=Ken|date=December 29, 1982|newspaper=The Washington Post|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1982, Swigert left International Gold and Minerals Limited to run for [[98th United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] in the new [[Colorado's 6th congressional district|6th district]] as a Republican. Swigert developed a [[malignant tumor]] in his right nasal passage, which he disclosed to voters. Doctors told him he would finish radiation treatments June 15 and make a complete recovery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43237205/the_daily_newsjournal/|title=Swigert Runs for Congress|newspaper=The Daily News-Journal|location=Murfreesboro, Tennessee|date=June 2, 1982|page=3|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He developed back pain in August and he was diagnosed with bone marrow cancer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43237866/longview_daily_news/|title=Ex-Astronaut Swigert Campaigns for Congress, Against Cancer|newspaper=Longview Daily News|location=Longview, Washington|date=October 27, 1982|page=A4|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> On November 2, 1982, he won the seat with 64% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43238193/the_orlando_sentinel/|title=Ex-Astronaut Fights Cancer, Coasts to Seat on Congress|newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel|location=Orlando, Florida|date=November 4, 1982|page=A15|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn December 19, seven weeks after the election, he was airlifted from his home in [[Littleton, Colorado|Littleton]] to [[MedStar Georgetown University Hospital|Georgetown University Hospital]] in Washington, D.C. He died of [[respiratory failure]] at its [[Vince Lombardi|Lombardi]] Cancer Center on December 27, seven days before the beginning of his congressional term.{{sfn|Chaikin|1998|p=606}}<ref name=jslfacn >{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vL9PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3wUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7024%2C7060665 |newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner |agency=Associated Press |title=Jack Swigert loses fight against cancer |date=December 28, 1982 |page=4D|via=Google News}}</ref> He was 51.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43237566/the_times/|title=Ex-Astronaut, Newly Elected to House, Dies|newspaper=The Times|location=Shreveport, Louisiana|date=December 29, 1982|via=Newspapers.com|page=12D|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nFifteen astronauts were among the thousand at his [[Military funeral|full military honors]]' funeral in Denver, presided by [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archbishop]] [[James Vincent Casey|James Casey]], which included a [[Missing man formation|missing man flyover]] by [[LTV A-7 Corsair II|A-7 Corsairs]] of the [[Colorado Air National Guard]].<ref name=bbabur>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UaAmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0YYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4950%2C3651281 |work=The Bulletin |location=Bend, Oregon|agency=UPI |title=Astronaut Swigert buried |date=January 5, 1983 |page=A4|via=Google News}}</ref> He&nbsp;is buried alongside his parents in [[Mount Olivet Cemetery (Wheat Ridge, Colorado)|Mount Olivet Cemetery]] in suburban [[Wheat Ridge, Colorado|Wheat Ridge]].<ref name=exageul>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=onEcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gVgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4892%2C1130882 |newspaper=Victoria Advocate |location=Victoria, Texas |agency=Associated Press |title=Ex-astronaut gets eulogized |date=January 5, 1983 |page=10D|via=Google News}}</ref>\n\n==Awards, honors, and organizations==\n[[File:Ap13-70-H-496HR.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Jack Swigert]]\n\nSwigert received the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] (AIAA) [[Octave Chanute Award]] for 1966 for his participation in demonstrating the Rogallo Wing as a feasible land landing system for returning space vehicles and astronauts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44059912/santa_maria_times/|title=Astronauts Honored at LA Air Banquet|newspaper=Santa Maria Times|location=Santa Maria, California|date=June 29, 1966|page=17|agency=UPI|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nPresident Richard Nixon awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] to the Apollo 13 crew shortly after the conclusion of their mission.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39764154/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|title=Heroes of Apollo 13 Welcomed by President and Loved Ones|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Philadelphia Enquirer|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|date=April 19, 1970|via=Newspapers.com|page=1}}</ref> Following a sparse parade, Swigert received the City of New York Gold Medal on June 3.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/06/04/121526687.html?pageNumber=27|title=Mayor Honors Apollo 13 Crew at Lincoln Center|last1=Sauro|first1=William E.|date=June 4, 1970|newspaper=The New York Times|page=27}}</ref> He received the City of [[Houston]] Medal for Valor, 1970.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39728029/clarionledger/|title=Space City Cover Society Plans Medal for Astronauts|newspaper=Clarion-Ledger|location=Jackson, Mississippi|date=May 5, 1970|page=7|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Swigert received the [[American Astronautical Society]] Flight Achievement Award for 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://astronautical.org/awards/armstrong/|title=Neil Armstrong Space Flight Achievement Award|website=American Astronautical Society|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> He was given University of Colorado-Boulder's Distinguished Engineering Alumnus Award in 1970.<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" /> Vice President Spiro Agnew presented the crews of Apollo 11, 12, and 13 with the [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44062092/arizona_republic/|title=Agnew Confers Awards on Crews of 3 Apollos|newspaper=Arizona Republic|location=Phoenix, Arizona|date=November 14, 1970|agency=Associated Press|page=23|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Apollo 13 crew also received the AIAA [[Haley Astronautics Award]] in 1971, which included a small monetary award and a medal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43358598/tucson_daily_citizen/|title=Astronauts to Get Top Award at Arizona Conference|newspaper=Tucson Daily Citizen|location=Tucson, Arizona|date=March 5, 1971|page=31|via=Newspapers.com|agency=UPI}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43588375/chicago_tribune/|title=Plane Talk|last1=Thomis|first1=Wayne|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=March 7, 1971|via=Newspapers.com|page=3-21}}</ref> Swigert was awarded the 1972 Antonian Gold Medal.<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" />\n\nHe was presented an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate of Science]] degree from [[American International College]] in 1970,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43824077/nashua_telegraph/|title=Honorary Degree for Astronaut|newspaper=Nashua Telegraph|location=Nashua, New Hampshire|date=June 6, 1970|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Associated Press|page=18}}</ref> an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate of Laws]] degree from [[Western State University]] in 1970,<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" /> and an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate of Science]] from [[Western Michigan University]] in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholarworks.wmich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1112&context=western_newsletter|title=Apollo 13 Astronauts Made Honorary WMU Alums|website=Western Michigan University Newsletter|access-date=September 12, 2019|date=September 1970}}</ref>\n\nSwigert was among 14 Apollo astronauts inducted into the [[New Mexico Museum of Space History|International Space Hall of Fame]] in 1983.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=83|title=Jack Swigert inducted into the International Space Hall of Fame|publisher=New Mexico Museum of Space History|access-date=November 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29964158/el_paso_times/|title=Space Hall Inducts 14 Apollo Program Astronauts|last1=Sheppard|first1=David|newspaper=El Paso Times|location=El Paso, Texas|date=October 2, 1983|page=18|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[Colorado Aviation Hall of Fame]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Holmes|editor-first1=Charles W.|title=Honoree Album of the Colorado Aviation Hall of Fame|year=1999|publisher=Audubon Media Corp.|location=Audubon, Iowa|oclc=53380391}}</ref> In 1997, Swigert, along with 23 other Apollo astronauts, was posthumously inducted into the [[United States Astronaut Hall of Fame|U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/john-l-swigert-jr/|title=Jack Swigert inducted into the U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame|access-date=November 27, 2017|publisher=Astronaut Scholarship Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28283877/florida_today/|title=Ceremony to Honor Astronauts|newspaper=Florida Today|location=Cocoa, Florida|page=2B|date=October 2, 1997|last1=Meyer|first1=Marilyn|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was elected in September 2003 to the [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] Alumni Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpi.edu/about/alumni/inductees/swigert.html |title=RPI Alumni Hall of Fame: John L. Swigert Jr |publisher=Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute|date= |accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43185900/hartford_courant/|title=Rensselaer Honors Late Apollo 13 Astronaut Swigert|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=October 21, 2003|page=B4|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Swigert was portrayed by [[Kevin Bacon]] in [[Ron Howard]]'s film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41798850/the_record/|title=America's Derring-Do Resurrected|last1=Ebert|first1=Robert|newspaper=The Record|location=Hackensack, New Jersey|date=June 30, 1995|page=43|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, a [[Jack Swigert (Lundeen)|statue of Swigert]] made by George and Mark Lundeen was placed on display in the [[U.S. Capitol Building]] as one of two statues given by the state of Colorado to the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43185619/albuquerque_journal/|title=Statuesque Nominee|last1=Calloway|first1=Larry|newspaper=Albuquerque Journal|location=Albuquerque, New Mexico|date=June 22, 1997|via=Newspapers.com|page=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aoc.gov/art/national-statuary-hall-collection/john-swigert-jr|title=John Swigert Jr.|website=Architect of the Capitol|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> As of December 2008 the statue is on display in Emancipation Hall in the [[United States Capitol Visitor Center]]. A duplicate statue is currently on display at [[Denver International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://denverite.com/2017/04/17/jack-swigert-astronaut-commemorated-dia-amazing-thing-45-years-ago/|title=Jack Swigert, the astronaut commemorated at DIA, did an amazing thing 47 years ago today|last1=Kenney|first1=Andrew|website=Denverite|access-date=January 28, 2020|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Space Foundation was founded in 1983 in part to honor the memory and accomplishments of Swigert.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203060101/http://www.nationalspacesymposium.org/symposium-awards|archive-date=February 3, 2009|access-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=dead|url=http://www.nationalspacesymposium.org/symposium-awards|title=Symposium Awards|publisher=National Space Symposium}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43227505/the_los_angeles_times/|title=JPL Honored for Space Exploration|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|location=Los Angeles, California|date=February 17, 2006|page=A8|via=Newspapers.com|last1=O'Keefe|first1=Mary}}</ref> In 2004, the Space Foundation launched the [[Space Foundation#John L. Jack, Swigert, Jr., Award for Space Exploration|John L. \"Jack\" Swigert Jr. Award for Space Exploration]], which is presented annually to an individual, group, or organization that has made a significant contribution to space exploration.  On August 18, 2009, the [[Space Foundation]] and Colorado Springs District 11 partnered to open the Jack Swigert Aerospace Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefoundation.org/media/press-releases/jack-swigert-aerospace-academy-opens |title=Jack Swigert Aerospace Academy Opens |publisher=Space Foundation |date = |accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.csbj.com/2009/08/18/jack-swigert-aerospace-academy-opens/|title=Jack Swigert Aerospace Academy opens|newspaper=The Colorado Springs Business Journal|last1=Baillie|first1=Amber|date=August 18, 2009|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSwigert was a member of numerous organizations. He was a [[fellow]] of the [[American Astronautical Society]]; associate fellow of the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] and the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]]; and member of the [[Quiet Birdmen]], [[Phi Gamma Delta]], [[Pi Tau Sigma]], and [[Sigma Tau]].<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Spaceflight|Solar System}}\n* [[Astronaut-politician]]\n* [[List of members-elect of the United States House of Representatives who never took their seats]]\n* [[List of spaceflight records]]\n* [[The Astronaut Monument]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n== Works cited ==\n*{{cite book|first=Andrew|last=Chaikin|authorlink=Andrew Chaikin|title=[[A Man on the Moon]]|publisher=[[Penguin Books Ltd]]|isbn=978-0-14-024146-4|year=1998|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lovell|first=James A. |editor-last=Cortright |editor-first=Edgar M.|title=Apollo Expeditions to the Moon|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19760005868.pdf|year=1975|publisher=NASA|location=Washington, D.C.|id=SP-350|chapter=Chapter 13: \"Houston, We've Had a Problem\"|chapter-url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19760005868.pdf#page=261|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kraft|first=Christopher|authorlink=Christopher Kraft|title=Flight: My Life in Mission Control|publisher=Dutton|year=2001|location=New York|isbn=978-0-525-94571-0|ref={{sfnRef|Kraft}}|url=https://archive.org/details/flight00chri}}\n* {{cite book|title=Deke! U.S. Manned Space: From Mercury to the Shuttle|last1=Slayton|first1=Donald K. \"Deke\"|authorlink1=Deke Slayton|last2=Cassutt|first2=Michael|authorlink2=Michael Cassutt|year=1994|edition=1st|publisher=[[Tor Books|Forge]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-312-85503-1|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dekeusmannedspac00slay}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jack Swigert}}\n*[http://www.uk.imdb.com/name/nm0842641/ Jack Swigert] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n{{People who have traveled to the Moon|state=expanded}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 5|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swigert, John Leonard}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:1970 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Jack Swigert]]\n[[Category:Apollo 13]]\n[[Category:American astronaut-politicians]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Apollo program astronauts]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Colorado Buffaloes football players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:Deaths from multiple myeloma]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Denver]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Hartford alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:United States Air National Guard]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Colorado]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Jack Swigert\n| birth_name    = John Leonard Swigert Jr.\n| image         = Jack Swigert- Apollo 13.jpg\n| image_size    = 230\n| caption       = Swigert in April 1970\n| office        = Member-elect of the <br /> [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] <br /> from [[Colorado]]'s [[Colorado's 6th congressional district|6th]] district\n| term         = '''''Died before taking office'''''\n| predecessor   = ''Constituency established''\n| successor     = [[Daniel Schaefer]] \n| nationality   = American\n| birth_date    = August 30, 1931\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1982|12|27|1931|8|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Denver]], Colorado, U.S.\n| death_place   = [[Washington D.C.]], U.S.\n| restingplace  = [[Mount Olivet Cemetery (Wheat Ridge)|Mount Olivet Cemetery]],<br />[[Wheat Ridge, Colorado]]\n| alma_mater    = {{unbulleted list|[[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]],<br />B.S. 1953|[[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], M.S. 1965|[[University of Hartford]],<br />MBA 1967}}\n| occupation    = [[Fighter pilot]], [[test pilot]], [[astronaut]]\n| party         = [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] \n|allegiance   = {{USA}}\n|branch       = [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] (1953\u20131956)\n|serviceyears = 1953\u20131965\n|rank         = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|25px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n|unit         = {{unbulleted list\n|[[Massachusetts Air National Guard]] (1957\u20131960)\n|[[Connecticut Air National Guard]] (1960\u20131965) \n}}\n|parents      = John L. Swigert, M.D.<br />Virginia Swigert\n| module = {{Infobox astronaut | child=yes\n   | image         = Jack Swigert.jpg\n   | type          = [[NASA]] astronaut\n   | selection     = [[NASA Astronaut Group 5|1966 NASA Group 5]]\n   | time          = 5d 22h 54m\n   | mission       = [[Apollo 13]]\n   | insignia      = [[Image:Apollo 13-insignia.png|45px]]\n   | Date of ret   = August 1977\n   | awards        = {{Presidential Medal of Freedom}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n   }}\n}}\n'''John Leonard Swigert Jr.''' (August 30, 1931 \u2013 December 27, 1982) was an American [[test pilot]], [[Mechanical engineering|mechanical]],[[aerospace engineer]], [[United States Air Force]] pilot, [[NASA]] [[astronaut]], and [[politician]]. In April 1970, as command module pilot of [[Apollo 13]], he became one of [[List of Apollo astronauts#Apollo astronauts who flew to the Moon without landing|twenty-four astronauts who flew to the Moon]].<ref name=exaschl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CVkvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9toFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1306%2C4053722 |newspaper=Beaver County Times |title=Ex-astronaut's challenge |last=Eicher |first=Diane |date=December 19, 1982 |page=B2|via=Google News}}</ref><ref name=nytobit>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/29/obituaries/jack-swigert-astronaut-elected-to-congress-dies.html |newspaper=The New York Times |title=Jack Swigert, astronaut elected to Congress, dies |last=Treaster |first=Joseph B. |date=December 29, 1982 |access-date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore joining NASA in 1966, Swigert was a civilian [[test pilot]] and [[fighter pilot]] in the [[Air National Guard]]. After leaving NASA, he lost a primary election against [[William L. Armstrong|Bill Armstrong]]. While running for [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]], he was diagnosed with cancer. He won the election for Colorado's new [[Colorado's 6th congressional district|6th district]], but died before being sworn in.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Leonard Swigert Jr. was born on August 30, 1931 in [[Denver]], Colorado to parents John Leonard Sr. (1903\u20131973) and Virginia Swigert (1906\u20131993). Swigert's father was an [[Ophthalmology|ophthalmologist]].<ref name=exaschl/><ref name=nytobit/> At the age of 14, he became fascinated by aviation. While he would have been content just watching planes take off from nearby Combs Field, young Jack became determined to do more than be a spectator. He took on a newspaper route to earn money for flying lessons, and by age 16 he was a [[Private pilot licence|licensed private pilot]].<ref name=\"americaspace\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americaspace.com/?p=66745|title=For Jack Swigert, On His 83rd Birthday|last1=Carney|first1=Emily|publisher=AmericaSpace|access-date=November 27, 2017|date=April 29, 2014}}</ref> He attended [[Blessed Sacrament School (Denver, Colorado)|Blessed Sacrament School]], [[Regis Jesuit High School]], and [[East High School (Denver)|East High School]], from which he graduated in 1949.<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html|title=John L. Swigert Jr., NASA Astronaut (Deceased)|publisher=NASA JSC|access-date=November 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143646/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html|archive-date=April 20, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSwigert received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[mechanical engineering]] from the [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] in 1953, where he also played [[American football|football]] for the [[Colorado Buffaloes football|Buffaloes]].<ref name=exaschl/><ref name=nytobit/> He later earned a [[Master of Science]] degree in [[aerospace engineering]] from the [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] (Hartford campus) in 1965,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43310515/hartford_courant/|title=Astronaut is Honored by Chamber, School|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=April 29, 1966|page=21|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[University of Hartford]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43311499/hartford_courant/|title=Astronaut Receives Degree|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=June 11, 1967|page=42|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nHis recreational interests included [[golf]], [[American handball|handball]], [[bowling]], [[skiing]], [[Human swimming|swimming]], and [[basketball]]. His hobbies included [[photography]].<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" />\n\nHe was a member of the [[Boy Scouts of America]] and attained the rank of [[Second Class (Boy Scouts of America)|Second Class Scout]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx|title=Scouting and Space Exploration|website=Boy Scouts of America|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000000/http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx |archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usscouts.org/eagle/eagleastronauts.asp |title=Astronauts with Scouting experience|publisher= US Scouting Service|date=August 26, 2012|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Flight experience==\n[[File:Apollo13 apparatus.jpg|thumb|left|Swigert, at right, with the \"mailbox\" rig improvised to adapt the Apollo 13 [[Apollo command module|command module]]'s square [[carbon dioxide]] scrubber cartridges to fit the [[lunar module]], which took a round cartridge]]\n\nFollowing his graduation from Colorado in 1953, Swigert joined the [[U.S. Air Force]]. Upon graduation from the Pilot Training Program and [[USAF Weapons School#Origins|Gunnery School]] at [[Nellis Air Force Base]], [[Nevada]], he was assigned as a [[fighter pilot]] in Japan and Korea. In 1953, he survived his plane crashing into a radar unit on a Korean airstrip.<ref name=\"americaspace\" /><ref name=nytobit/>\n\nAfter completing his tour of active duty in the Air Force, he served as a jet fighter pilot with the [[Massachusetts Air National Guard|Massachusetts]] (1957\u20131960) and [[Connecticut Air National Guard]] (1960\u20131965).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43823204/abilene_reporternews/|title=Astronaut Swigert Began Flight Instruction at 14|newspaper=Abilene Reporter-News|location=Abilene, Texas|date=May 17, 1968|page=B-1|via=Newspapers.com|last1=Kershaw|first1=Tom}}</ref> Swigert held a position as engineering test pilot for [[North American Aviation]] before joining NASA. He was previously an engineering test pilot for [[Pratt & Whitney]], from February 1957 to June 1964.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43822825/page_e1/|title=A Tribute: He 'Bore Holes in the Sky'|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=April 14, 1983|via=Newspapers.com|page=E1|last1=Pallatto|first1=John}}</ref>\n\nHe logged over 7,200 hours in flight, with more than 5,725 in [[jet aircraft]].<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\"/>\n\n==NASA career==\nAfter unsuccessfully applying for NASA's [[Astronaut Group 2|second]] and [[Astronaut Group 3|third]] astronaut selections,{{sfn|Chaikin|1998|p=307}} Swigert was accepted into the [[NASA Astronaut Corps]] as part of [[NASA Astronaut Group 5]] in April 1966.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28240973/the_high_point_enterprise/|title=19 New Spacemen Are Named|last1=Thompson|first1=Ronald|newspaper=The High Point Enterprise|location=High Point, North Carolina|date=April 5, 1966|page=2A|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Swigert became a specialist on the [[Apollo command module]]: he was one of the few astronauts who requested to be command module pilots.{{sfn|Chaikin|1998|p=307}}\n\nSwigert was a member of [[Apollo 7]]'s astronaut support crew, the first support crew for an Apollo mission.<ref name=atp>{{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/20319-jack-swigert-apollo-13-biography.html|title=Jack Swigert: Apollo 13 Astronaut Turned Politician|last1=Howell|first1=Elizabeth|date=March 20, 2013|access-date=January 28, 2020|website=Space.com}}</ref>\n\n===Apollo 13===\n{{Main|Apollo 13}}\nSwigert was one of three astronauts aboard the [[Apollo 13]] Moon mission launched April 11, 1970. Originally part of the backup crew for the mission, he was assigned to the mission three days before launch, replacing astronaut [[Ken Mattingly]]. The prime crew had been exposed to [[German Measles]] (the rubella virus) from [[Charles Duke]] and, because Mattingly had no immunity to the disease, NASA did not want to risk his falling ill during critical phases of the flight.{{sfn|Slayton|Cassutt|1994|p=256}}\n\nThe mission was the third crewed lunar-landing attempt, but was aborted after the rupture of an oxygen tank in the spacecraft's [[Apollo service module|service module]]. Swigert was the astronaut who made the dramatic announcement, \"[[Houston, we have a problem|Houston, we've had a problem here]]\".{{sfn|Lovell|1975}} The statement was then repeated by commander of the flight [[Jim Lovell]]. Swigert, along with fellow astronauts Lovell and [[Fred Haise]], traveled around the Moon and returned safely to Earth on April 17 after about 5 days and 23 hours, and received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=2472|title=Remarks on Presenting the Presidential Medal of Freedom to Apollo 13 Astronauts in Honolulu|publisher=The American Presidency Project|access-date=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Apollo\u2013Soyuz Test Project ===\nNASA Director of Flight Crew Operations [[Deke Slayton]], who selected the astronauts, recommended Swigert as [[command module pilot]] for the [[Apollo\u2013Soyuz Test Project]], the first joint mission with the Soviet Union. Slayton felt Swigert deserved another chance to fly after having been selected for Apollo 13 two days before launch, and performing well.{{sfn|Slayton|Cassutt|1994|p=278}}\n\nDuring 1972, the [[Apollo 15 postal covers incident]] caused NASA investigators to inquire into other astronauts.<ref name=\"americaspace\" /> A number of Apollo astronauts, including Swigert, had made agreements with West German stamp dealer Hermann Sieger, whose brainchild the [[Apollo 15]] covers was, to autograph philatelic items in exchange for a payment of about $2,500. Swigert originally denied involvement when interviewed by NASA investigators.{{sfn|Slayton|Cassutt|1994|p=279}} According to [[Christopher C. Kraft]], the investigators subpoenaed his bank records, finding more funds than expected, and records of a predated charitable donation.{{sfn|Kraft|p=344}} Swigert's subsequent admission caused NASA Deputy Administrator [[George M. Low]] to remove him from Apollo\u2013Soyuz.<ref name=\"americaspace\" />\n\n==Post-NASA career==\nAware that his spaceflight career was most likely over,<ref name=\"americaspace\" /> Swigert took a leave of absence from NASA in April 1973 to become executive director of the [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science and Astronautics]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"nmmuseum\" />\n\nSwigert eventually left NASA and the committee in August 1977 to enter politics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43299511/the_paducah_sun/|title=People...In the News|newspaper=The Paducah Sun|location=Paducah, Kentucky|date=September 27, 1977|page=3A|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He ran for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in 1978, but was soundly defeated in the Republican primary in September <!--12-->by [[Colorado's 5th congressional district|congressman]] [[William L. Armstrong|Bill Armstrong]].<ref name=pktmincm>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eiVVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-X8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5168%2C2943019 |work=Deseret News |location=Salt Lake City, Utah|agency=UPI |title=Primaries kind to most incumbents |date=September 13, 1978 |page=A-1|via=Google News}}</ref><!-- https://www.sos.state.co.us/pubs/elections/Results/Abstract/pdf/1900-1999/1978AbstractBook.pdf --> In 1979, Swigert became vice president of B.D.M. Corporation in [[Golden, Colorado|Golden]].<ref name=atp /> He left <!--BDM-->in 1981 to join International Gold and Minerals Limited as vice president for financial and corporate affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1982/12/29/rep-elect-swigert-dies/5f746229-6c2e-498b-a514-7ab426aef1ff/|title=Rep.-Elect Swigert Dies|last1=Ringle|first1=Ken|date=December 29, 1982|newspaper=The Washington Post|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1982, Swigert left International Gold and Minerals Limited to run for [[98th United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] in the new [[Colorado's 6th congressional district|6th district]] as a Republican. Swigert developed a [[malignant tumor]] in his right nasal passage, which he disclosed to voters. Doctors told him he would finish radiation treatments June 15 and make a complete recovery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43237205/the_daily_newsjournal/|title=Swigert Runs for Congress|newspaper=The Daily News-Journal|location=Murfreesboro, Tennessee|date=June 2, 1982|page=3|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He developed back pain in August and he was diagnosed with bone marrow cancer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43237866/longview_daily_news/|title=Ex-Astronaut Swigert Campaigns for Congress, Against Cancer|newspaper=Longview Daily News|location=Longview, Washington|date=October 27, 1982|page=A4|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> On November 2, 1982, he won the seat with 64% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43238193/the_orlando_sentinel/|title=Ex-Astronaut Fights Cancer, Coasts to Seat on Congress|newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel|location=Orlando, Florida|date=November 4, 1982|page=A15|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn December 19, seven weeks after the election, he was airlifted from his home in [[Littleton, Colorado|Littleton]] to [[MedStar Georgetown University Hospital|Georgetown University Hospital]] in Washington, D.C. He died of [[respiratory failure]] at its [[Vince Lombardi|Lombardi]] Cancer Center on December 27, seven days before the beginning of his congressional term.{{sfn|Chaikin|1998|p=606}}<ref name=jslfacn >{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vL9PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3wUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7024%2C7060665 |newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner |agency=Associated Press |title=Jack Swigert loses fight against cancer |date=December 28, 1982 |page=4D|via=Google News}}</ref> He was 51.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43237566/the_times/|title=Ex-Astronaut, Newly Elected to House, Dies|newspaper=The Times|location=Shreveport, Louisiana|date=December 29, 1982|via=Newspapers.com|page=12D|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nFifteen astronauts were among the thousand at his [[Military funeral|full military honors]]' funeral in Denver, presided by [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archbishop]] [[James Vincent Casey|James Casey]], which included a [[Missing man formation|missing man flyover]] by [[LTV A-7 Corsair II|A-7 Corsairs]] of the [[Colorado Air National Guard]].<ref name=bbabur>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UaAmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0YYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4950%2C3651281 |work=The Bulletin |location=Bend, Oregon|agency=UPI |title=Astronaut Swigert buried |date=January 5, 1983 |page=A4|via=Google News}}</ref> He&nbsp;is buried alongside his parents in [[Mount Olivet Cemetery (Wheat Ridge, Colorado)|Mount Olivet Cemetery]] in suburban [[Wheat Ridge, Colorado|Wheat Ridge]].<ref name=exageul>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=onEcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gVgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4892%2C1130882 |newspaper=Victoria Advocate |location=Victoria, Texas |agency=Associated Press |title=Ex-astronaut gets eulogized |date=January 5, 1983 |page=10D|via=Google News}}</ref>\n\n==Awards, honors, and organizations==\n[[File:Ap13-70-H-496HR.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Jack Swigert]]\n\nSwigert received the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] (AIAA) [[Octave Chanute Award]] for 1966 for his participation in demonstrating the Rogallo Wing as a feasible land landing system for returning space vehicles and astronauts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44059912/santa_maria_times/|title=Astronauts Honored at LA Air Banquet|newspaper=Santa Maria Times|location=Santa Maria, California|date=June 29, 1966|page=17|agency=UPI|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nPresident Richard Nixon awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] to the Apollo 13 crew shortly after the conclusion of their mission.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39764154/the_philadelphia_inquirer/|title=Heroes of Apollo 13 Welcomed by President and Loved Ones|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Philadelphia Enquirer|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|date=April 19, 1970|via=Newspapers.com|page=1}}</ref> Following a sparse parade, Swigert received the City of New York Gold Medal on June 3.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/06/04/121526687.html?pageNumber=27|title=Mayor Honors Apollo 13 Crew at Lincoln Center|last1=Sauro|first1=William E.|date=June 4, 1970|newspaper=The New York Times|page=27}}</ref> He received the City of [[Houston]] Medal for Valor, 1970.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39728029/clarionledger/|title=Space City Cover Society Plans Medal for Astronauts|newspaper=Clarion-Ledger|location=Jackson, Mississippi|date=May 5, 1970|page=7|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Swigert received the [[American Astronautical Society]] Flight Achievement Award for 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://astronautical.org/awards/armstrong/|title=Neil Armstrong Space Flight Achievement Award|website=American Astronautical Society|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> He was given University of Colorado-Boulder's Distinguished Engineering Alumnus Award in 1970.<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" /> Vice President Spiro Agnew presented the crews of Apollo 11, 12, and 13 with the [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/44062092/arizona_republic/|title=Agnew Confers Awards on Crews of 3 Apollos|newspaper=Arizona Republic|location=Phoenix, Arizona|date=November 14, 1970|agency=Associated Press|page=23|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Apollo 13 crew also received the AIAA [[Haley Astronautics Award]] in 1971, which included a small monetary award and a medal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43358598/tucson_daily_citizen/|title=Astronauts to Get Top Award at Arizona Conference|newspaper=Tucson Daily Citizen|location=Tucson, Arizona|date=March 5, 1971|page=31|via=Newspapers.com|agency=UPI}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43588375/chicago_tribune/|title=Plane Talk|last1=Thomis|first1=Wayne|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=March 7, 1971|via=Newspapers.com|page=3-21}}</ref> Swigert was awarded the 1972 Antonian Gold Medal.<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" />\n\nHe was presented an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate of Science]] degree from [[American International College]] in 1970,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43824077/nashua_telegraph/|title=Honorary Degree for Astronaut|newspaper=Nashua Telegraph|location=Nashua, New Hampshire|date=June 6, 1970|via=Newspapers.com|agency=Associated Press|page=18}}</ref> an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate of Laws]] degree from [[Western State University]] in 1970,<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" /> and an [[Honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate of Science]] from [[Western Michigan University]] in 1970.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholarworks.wmich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1112&context=western_newsletter|title=Apollo 13 Astronauts Made Honorary WMU Alums|website=Western Michigan University Newsletter|access-date=September 12, 2019|date=September 1970}}</ref>\n\nSwigert was among 14 Apollo astronauts inducted into the [[New Mexico Museum of Space History|International Space Hall of Fame]] in 1983.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=83|title=Jack Swigert inducted into the International Space Hall of Fame|publisher=New Mexico Museum of Space History|access-date=November 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29964158/el_paso_times/|title=Space Hall Inducts 14 Apollo Program Astronauts|last1=Sheppard|first1=David|newspaper=El Paso Times|location=El Paso, Texas|date=October 2, 1983|page=18|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[Colorado Aviation Hall of Fame]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Holmes|editor-first1=Charles W.|title=Honoree Album of the Colorado Aviation Hall of Fame|year=1999|publisher=Audubon Media Corp.|location=Audubon, Iowa|oclc=53380391}}</ref> In 1997, Swigert, along with 23 other Apollo astronauts, was posthumously inducted into the [[United States Astronaut Hall of Fame|U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/john-l-swigert-jr/|title=Jack Swigert inducted into the U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame|access-date=November 27, 2017|publisher=Astronaut Scholarship Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28283877/florida_today/|title=Ceremony to Honor Astronauts|newspaper=Florida Today|location=Cocoa, Florida|page=2B|date=October 2, 1997|last1=Meyer|first1=Marilyn|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was elected in September 2003 to the [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] Alumni Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpi.edu/about/alumni/inductees/swigert.html |title=RPI Alumni Hall of Fame: John L. Swigert Jr |publisher=Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute|date= |accessdate=2012-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43185900/hartford_courant/|title=Rensselaer Honors Late Apollo 13 Astronaut Swigert|newspaper=Hartford Courant|location=Hartford, Connecticut|date=October 21, 2003|page=B4|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Swigert was portrayed by [[Kevin Bacon]] in [[Ron Howard]]'s film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41798850/the_record/|title=America's Derring-Do Resurrected|last1=Ebert|first1=Robert|newspaper=The Record|location=Hackensack, New Jersey|date=June 30, 1995|page=43|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, a [[Jack Swigert (Lundeen)|statue of Swigert]] made by George and Mark Lundeen was placed on display in the [[U.S. Capitol Building]] as one of two statues given by the state of Colorado to the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43185619/albuquerque_journal/|title=Statuesque Nominee|last1=Calloway|first1=Larry|newspaper=Albuquerque Journal|location=Albuquerque, New Mexico|date=June 22, 1997|via=Newspapers.com|page=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aoc.gov/art/national-statuary-hall-collection/john-swigert-jr|title=John Swigert Jr.|website=Architect of the Capitol|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> As of December 2008 the statue is on display in Emancipation Hall in the [[United States Capitol Visitor Center]]. A duplicate statue is currently on display at [[Denver International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://denverite.com/2017/04/17/jack-swigert-astronaut-commemorated-dia-amazing-thing-45-years-ago/|title=Jack Swigert, the astronaut commemorated at DIA, did an amazing thing 47 years ago today|last1=Kenney|first1=Andrew|website=Denverite|access-date=January 28, 2020|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Space Foundation was founded in 1983 in part to honor the memory and accomplishments of Swigert.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203060101/http://www.nationalspacesymposium.org/symposium-awards|archive-date=February 3, 2009|access-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=dead|url=http://www.nationalspacesymposium.org/symposium-awards|title=Symposium Awards|publisher=National Space Symposium}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43227505/the_los_angeles_times/|title=JPL Honored for Space Exploration|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|location=Los Angeles, California|date=February 17, 2006|page=A8|via=Newspapers.com|last1=O'Keefe|first1=Mary}}</ref> In 2004, the Space Foundation launched the [[Space Foundation#John L. Jack, Swigert, Jr., Award for Space Exploration|John L. \"Jack\" Swigert Jr. Award for Space Exploration]], which is presented annually to an individual, group, or organization that has made a significant contribution to space exploration.  On August 18, 2009, the [[Space Foundation]] and Colorado Springs District 11 partnered to open the Jack Swigert Aerospace Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacefoundation.org/media/press-releases/jack-swigert-aerospace-academy-opens |title=Jack Swigert Aerospace Academy Opens |publisher=Space Foundation |date = |accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.csbj.com/2009/08/18/jack-swigert-aerospace-academy-opens/|title=Jack Swigert Aerospace Academy opens|newspaper=The Colorado Springs Business Journal|last1=Baillie|first1=Amber|date=August 18, 2009|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSwigert was a member of numerous organizations. He was a [[fellow]] of the [[American Astronautical Society]]; associate fellow of the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] and the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]]; and member of the [[Quiet Birdmen]], [[Phi Gamma Delta]], [[Pi Tau Sigma]], and [[Sigma Tau]].<ref name=\"jsc.nasa.gov\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Spaceflight|Solar System}}\n* [[Astronaut-politician]]\n* [[List of members-elect of the United States House of Representatives who never took their seats]]\n* [[List of spaceflight records]]\n* [[The Astronaut Monument]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n== Works cited ==\n*{{cite book|first=Andrew|last=Chaikin|authorlink=Andrew Chaikin|title=[[A Man on the Moon]]|publisher=[[Penguin Books Ltd]]|isbn=978-0-14-024146-4|year=1998|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lovell|first=James A. |editor-last=Cortright |editor-first=Edgar M.|title=Apollo Expeditions to the Moon|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19760005868.pdf|year=1975|publisher=NASA|location=Washington, D.C.|id=SP-350|chapter=Chapter 13: \"Houston, We've Had a Problem\"|chapter-url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19760005868.pdf#page=261|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kraft|first=Christopher|authorlink=Christopher Kraft|title=Flight: My Life in Mission Control|publisher=Dutton|year=2001|location=New York|isbn=978-0-525-94571-0|ref={{sfnRef|Kraft}}|url=https://archive.org/details/flight00chri}}\n* {{cite book|title=Deke! U.S. Manned Space: From Mercury to the Shuttle|last1=Slayton|first1=Donald K. \"Deke\"|authorlink1=Deke Slayton|last2=Cassutt|first2=Michael|authorlink2=Michael Cassutt|year=1994|edition=1st|publisher=[[Tor Books|Forge]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-312-85503-1|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dekeusmannedspac00slay}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jack Swigert}}\n*[http://www.uk.imdb.com/name/nm0842641/ Jack Swigert] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n{{People who have traveled to the Moon|state=expanded}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 5|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swigert, John Leonard}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:1970 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Jack Swigert]]\n[[Category:Apollo 13]]\n[[Category:American astronaut-politicians]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Apollo program astronauts]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Colorado Buffaloes football players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:Deaths from multiple myeloma]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Denver]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder alumni]]\n[[Category:Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Hartford alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:United States Air National Guard]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Colorado]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American engineers]]\n", "name_user": "Once in a Lifetime", "label": "safe", "comment": "Missing space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Swigert"}
{"title_page": "Rushop", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|static_image             = Rushop hall 087176 0ec1e6c0.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 240px\n|static_image_caption=Rushop Hall\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.34|-1.86|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type                 = Derbyshire\n|official_name            = Rushop\n|population               = \n|shire_district           = [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]]\n| shire_county            = [[Derbyshire]]\n|region                   = East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = \n|post_town                = HIGH PEAK\n|postcode_district        = SK23\n|postcode_area            = SK\n|dial_code                =01298\n|os_grid_reference        = SK094825\n}}\n\n'''Rushop''' or '''Rushup'''<ref>Marked as \"Rushop\" on the modern Ordnance Survey map and the house sign, but all the nearby features sharing this name (Rushup Farm, [[Rushup Edge]] etc.) use the \"Rushup\" spelling, as does the 1940s map.</ref> is a small North [[Derbyshire]] village. It is in the town of Chapel-en-le-Frith.\n[[Agriculture]] has until recently been the main occupation in the village. At present very few of the residents work in Rushop and several of the houses are second homes only occupied at weekends and holidays.\n\nThe village church of St Cuthbert dates from the mid-17th century, but excavations in the 1840s revealed a much older building possibly the 10th-century church erected to the king and saint [[Pabo Post Prydain]].\n\nThere is archaeological and documentary evidence that there was a settlement at this site since before the [[Roman invasion of Britain]]. The settlement is alleged to have been a [[Britain in the Middle Ages|British]] village, under nominal [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo Saxon]] rule after the fall of the area to [[Angles]] from [[Bernicia]] around 590, mainly due to the lack of Anglo Saxon placenames in the valley and the presence of names, such as Eccles, Inch and Pen-, which have origins in a [[Brythonic languages|Brythonic]] language of [[Great Britain|Britain]].\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Rushup, Derbyshire|Rushop}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Chapel-en-le-Frith]]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|static_image             = Rushop hall 087176 0ec1e6c0.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 240px\n|static_image_caption=Rushop Hall\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.34|-1.86|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type                 = Derbyshire\n|official_name            = Rushop\n|population               = \n|shire_district           = [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]]\n| shire_county            = [[Derbyshire]]\n|region                   = East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = \n|post_town                = HIGH PEAK\n|postcode_district        = SK23\n|postcode_area            = SK\n|dial_code                =01298\n|os_grid_reference        = SK094825\n}}\n\n'''Rushop''' or '''Rushup'''<ref>Marked as \"Rushop\" on the modern Ordnance Survey map and the house sign, but all the nearby features sharing this name (Rushup Farm, [[Rushup Edge]] etc.) use the \"Rushup\" spelling, as does the 1940s map.</ref> is a small North [[Derbyshire]] village. It is in the town of Chapel-en-le-Frith.\n[[Agriculture]] has until recently been the main occupation in the village. At present very few of the residents work in Rushop and several of the houses are second homes only occupied at weekends and holidays.\n\nThe village church of St Cuthbert dates from the mid-17th century, but excavations in the 1840s revealed a much older building possibly the 10th-century church erected to the king and saint [[Pabo Post Prydain]].\n\nThere is archaeological and documentary evidence that there was a settlement at this site since before the [[Roman invasion of Britain]]. The settlement is alleged to have been a [[Britain in the Middle Ages|British]] village, under nominal [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo Saxon]] rule after the fall of the area to [[Angles]] from [[Bernicia]] around 590, mainly due to the lack of Anglo Saxon placenames in the valley and the presence of names, such as Eccles, Inch and Pen-, which have origins in a [[Brythonic languages|Brythonic]] language of [[Great Britain|Britain]].\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Rushup, Derbyshire|Rushop}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Chapel-en-le-Frith]]\n\n\n{{Derbyshire-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak, Derbyshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rushop"}
{"title_page": "New Mills Central railway station", "text_new": "{{short description|Railway station in Derbyshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| name         = New Mills Central\n| code         = NMC\n| image_name   = NewMillsCentral.JPG\n| caption      = New Mills Central in 2009\n| manager      = [[Northern Trains]]\n| locale       = [[New Mills]]\n| borough      = [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]]\n<!-- | lowusage0405 = {{pad|1em}}81,551\n| lowusage0506 = {{decrease}} 77,644\n| lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 81,078\n| lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 83,717\n| lowusage0809 = {{increase}} 133,004\n| lowusage0910 = {{increase}} 140,558\n| lowusage1011 = {{increase}} 146,018\n| lowusage1112 = {{increase}} 156,248\n| usage1213 = {{increase}} 0.214\n| usage1314 = {{decrease}} 0.205 -->\n| usage1415 = {{decrease}} 0.201\n| usage1516 = {{decrease}} 0.198\n| usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.209\n| usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.219\n| usage1819 = {{decrease}} 0.214\n| lowint1819 = {{pad|2em}} 3,673\n| platforms    = 2\n| gridref      = SJ997853\n| dft_category = E\n| original     = [[Marple, New Mills and Hayfield Junction Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[Great Central and Midland Joint Committee]]\n| postgroup    = Great Central and Midland Joint Committee\n| years1       = {{start date|1865|07|01|df=y}}\n| events1      = Opened as ''New Mills''\n| years2       = 25 August 1952\n| events2      = Renamed ''New Mills Central''\n}}\n\n'''New Mills Central railway station''' serves the town of [[New Mills]] in [[Derbyshire]], England. It is on the [[Hope Valley Line]] between [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly]] and [[Sheffield railway station|Sheffield]], {{convert|12+3/4|mi|km}} east of the former. The town is also served by [[New Mills Newtown railway station|New Mills Newtown]] station on the [[Buxton Line|Buxton to Stockport and Manchester line.]]\n\n==History==\n[[File:1970 New Mills Central station.jpg|thumb|left|The sign and canopy have changed since this 1970 photo]]\nIn the mid-19th century, the [[Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway]]  ran as far as [[Rowsley]], and was  extended by the [[Midland Railway]] to [[Buxton railway station|Buxton]], in its aim to run as far as [[Manchester]]. The  [[Manchester, Sheffield & Lincolnshire Railway]] also wished to extend southwards from its main line through [[Woodhead Tunnel]] to [[Sheffield]], and had built a branch to [[Hyde Central railway station|Hyde]]. The [[London and North Western Railway]] had meanwhile constructed their own line to Buxton from [[Whaley Bridge]] (with a station at [[New Mills Newtown railway station|Newtown]]) which effectively blocked the other two.\n\nAn agreement was reached whereby  the MS&LR would build their proposed \"Marple, New Mills and Hayfield Junction Railway\", while the Midland would extend  its line to New Mills from [[Millers Dale railway station|Millers Dale]] via [[Chinley railway station|Chinley]].  Passenger services began to [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] in 1868 and the line came under joint control as the [[Sheffield and Midland Railway Companies' Committee]] in 1870, while the Midland's line opened in 1867.\n\nAlthough the [[Hayfield branch]] is now closed, as is the tunnel (though a stub of the old branch line through the tunnel was used for some years afterwards as a turnback siding for trains terminating here), users can still travel most of its route on foot, bicycle or horse, along what is now known as the [[Sett Valley Trail]].\n\n==Station==\n[[File:New Mills Central station, May 1980.jpg|thumb|left|New Mills Central station, May 1980]]\nThe [[railway station|station]] lies at the junction of what was the Hayfield branch and the Midland line, the two appearing through tunnels, on a ledge blasted out of the cliff face, some forty feet above the [[River Goyt]].\n\nThe buildings on the down side still exist, as does the stationmaster's house built in 1864. The London line from [[Millers Dale railway station|Millers Dale]] closed in 1967 and the Hayfield branch closed in January 1970, but the station still supports the [[Hope Valley Line]] local service from Sheffield to Manchester.  Stopping trains from Sheffield formerly terminated here and those passengers wishing to travel onwards to Manchester had to change trains (most express services from Sheffield to Manchester ran through without stopping).  This practice ceased, however, when through trains were diverted via Hazel Grove and [[Stockport railway station|Stockport]] in 1986.\n\nThe station does, however, remain a terminus for many services from the Manchester direction \u2014 these can now return directly from the eastbound platform following signalling alterations in 2007 that also saw the remaining semaphore signals at the station replaced by colour lights.  A siding remains at the Marple end of the station to enable empty DMUs to be stabled clear of the main line.\n\nThe booking office on platform 1 is staffed six days per week, from early morning until early afternoon; outside these times, tickets must be bought on the train or in advance of travel.{{update inline|reason=Station now has a ticket machine; ticket office hours are probably less than stated|date=January 2020}}  Train running details are offered via automated announcements, digital display screens and timetable posters.  No level access is available: access to the booking office and platform 1 is via a steep lane from the main road, while platform 2 is accessed by means of a path and flight of steps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/nmc/details.html |title=New Mills Central (NMC) |publisher=National Rail Enquiries |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThere is now a half-hourly service to Manchester Piccadilly northbound on weekdays and an hourly stopping service to Sheffield. An hourly service operates in both directions on a Sunday.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2019|78}}</ref>\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=National Rail}}\n{{s-rail-national|toc=Northern Trains|route=[[Hope Valley Line]]|previous=Chinley|next=Strines}}\n{{s-rail-national|toc=Northern Trains|route=[[Hope Valley Line]]|next=Strines}}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line |previous={{stnlnk|Buxworth}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |next={{stnlnk|Strines}}<br /><small>Line and station open</small> |route=[[Midland Railway]] |col={{MR colour}} }}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line two routes |previous={{stnlnk|Birch Vale}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next={{stnlnk|Strines}}<br /><small>Line and station open</small> |route1=[[Great Central Railway]]<br /><small>[[Sheffield and Midland Railway Companies' Committee]]</small> |route2=[[Midland Railway]]<br /><small>[[Sheffield and Midland Railway Companies' Committee]]</small> |col1={{GCR colour}} |col2={{MR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Radford |first=B. |date=1988 |title=Midland Through the Peak: A Pictorial History of the Midland Railway Main Line Routes Between Derby and Manch |publisher=Unicorn Books |isbn=1852410019}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|New Mills Central railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|NMC|SK223JB}}\n*[http://www.railbrit.co.uk/location.php?loc=New%20Mills%20Central RAILSCOT - New Mills Central]\n\n{{Derbyshire stations}}\n{{High Peak}}\n{{coord|53.365|N|2.006|W|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central and Midland Joint Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1865]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:New Mills]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Railway station in Derbyshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| name         = New Mills Central\n| code         = NMC\n| image_name   = NewMillsCentral.JPG\n| caption      = New Mills Central in 2009\n| manager      = [[Northern Trains]]\n| locale       = [[New Mills]]\n| borough      = [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]]\n<!-- | lowusage0405 = {{pad|1em}}81,551\n| lowusage0506 = {{decrease}} 77,644\n| lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 81,078\n| lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 83,717\n| lowusage0809 = {{increase}} 133,004\n| lowusage0910 = {{increase}} 140,558\n| lowusage1011 = {{increase}} 146,018\n| lowusage1112 = {{increase}} 156,248\n| usage1213 = {{increase}} 0.214\n| usage1314 = {{decrease}} 0.205 -->\n| usage1415 = {{decrease}} 0.201\n| usage1516 = {{decrease}} 0.198\n| usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.209\n| usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.219\n| usage1819 = {{decrease}} 0.214\n| lowint1819 = {{pad|2em}} 3,673\n| platforms    = 2\n| gridref      = SJ997853\n| dft_category = E\n| original     = [[Marple, New Mills and Hayfield Junction Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[Great Central and Midland Joint Committee]]\n| postgroup    = Great Central and Midland Joint Committee\n| years1       = {{start date|1865|07|01|df=y}}\n| events1      = Opened as ''New Mills''\n| years2       = 25 August 1952\n| events2      = Renamed ''New Mills Central''\n}}\n\n'''New Mills Central railway station''' serves the town of [[New Mills]] in [[Derbyshire]], England. It is on the [[Hope Valley Line]] between [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly]] and [[Sheffield railway station|Sheffield]], {{convert|12+3/4|mi|km}} east of the former. The town is also served by [[New Mills Newtown railway station|New Mills Newtown]] station on the [[Buxton Line|Buxton to Stockport and Manchester line.]]\n\n==History==\n[[File:1970 New Mills Central station.jpg|thumb|left|The sign and canopy have changed since this 1970 photo]]\nIn the mid-19th century, the [[Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway]]  ran as far as [[Rowsley]], and was  extended by the [[Midland Railway]] to [[Buxton railway station|Buxton]], in its aim to run as far as [[Manchester]]. The  [[Manchester, Sheffield & Lincolnshire Railway]] also wished to extend southwards from its main line through [[Woodhead Tunnel]] to [[Sheffield]], and had built a branch to [[Hyde Central railway station|Hyde]]. The [[London and North Western Railway]] had meanwhile constructed their own line to Buxton from [[Whaley Bridge]] (with a station at [[New Mills Newtown railway station|Newtown]]) which effectively blocked the other two.\n\nAn agreement was reached whereby  the MS&LR would build their proposed \"Marple, New Mills and Hayfield Junction Railway\", while the Midland would extend  its line to New Mills from [[Millers Dale railway station|Millers Dale]] via [[Chinley railway station|Chinley]].  Passenger services began to [[Hayfield, Derbyshire|Hayfield]] in 1868 and the line came under joint control as the [[Sheffield and Midland Railway Companies' Committee]] in 1870, while the Midland's line opened in 1867.\n\nAlthough the [[Hayfield branch]] is now closed, as is the tunnel (though a stub of the old branch line through the tunnel was used for some years afterwards as a turnback siding for trains terminating here), users can still travel most of its route on foot, bicycle or horse, along what is now known as the [[Sett Valley Trail]].\n\n==Station==\n[[File:New Mills Central station, May 1980.jpg|thumb|left|New Mills Central station, May 1980]]\nThe [[railway station|station]] lies at the junction of what was the Hayfield branch and the Midland line, the two appearing through tunnels, on a ledge blasted out of the cliff face, some forty feet above the [[River Goyt]].\n\nThe buildings on the down side still exist, as does the stationmaster's house built in 1864. The London line from [[Millers Dale railway station|Millers Dale]] closed in 1967 and the Hayfield branch closed in January 1970, but the station still supports the [[Hope Valley Line]] local service from Sheffield to Manchester.  Stopping trains from Sheffield formerly terminated here and those passengers wishing to travel onwards to Manchester had to change trains (most express services from Sheffield to Manchester ran through without stopping).  This practice ceased, however, when through trains were diverted via Hazel Grove and [[Stockport railway station|Stockport]] in 1986.\n\nThe station does, however, remain a terminus for many services from the Manchester direction \u2014 these can now return directly from the eastbound platform following signalling alterations in 2007 that also saw the remaining semaphore signals at the station replaced by colour lights.  A siding remains at the Marple end of the station to enable empty DMUs to be stabled clear of the main line.\n\nThe booking office on platform 1 is staffed six days per week, from early morning until early afternoon; outside these times, tickets must be bought on the train or in advance of travel.{{update inline|reason=Station now has a ticket machine; ticket office hours are probably less than stated|date=January 2020}}  Train running details are offered via automated announcements, digital display screens and timetable posters.  No level access is available: access to the booking office and platform 1 is via a steep lane from the main road, while platform 2 is accessed by means of a path and flight of steps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/nmc/details.html |title=New Mills Central (NMC) |publisher=National Rail Enquiries |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThere is now a half-hourly service to Manchester Piccadilly northbound on weekdays and an hourly stopping service to Sheffield. An hourly service operates in both directions on a Sunday.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2019|78}}</ref>\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=National Rail}}\n{{s-rail-national|toc=Northern Trains|route=[[Hope Valley Line]]|previous=Chinley|next=Strines}}\n{{s-rail-national|toc=Northern Trains|route=[[Hope Valley Line]]|next=Strines}}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line |previous={{stnlnk|Buxworth}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |next={{stnlnk|Strines}}<br /><small>Line and station open</small> |route=[[Midland Railway]] |col={{MR colour}} }}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line two routes |previous={{stnlnk|Birch Vale}}<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next={{stnlnk|Strines}}<br /><small>Line and station open</small> |route1=[[Great Central Railway]]<br /><small>[[Sheffield and Midland Railway Companies' Committee]]</small> |route2=[[Midland Railway]]<br /><small>[[Sheffield and Midland Railway Companies' Committee]]</small> |col1={{GCR colour}} |col2={{MR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Radford |first=B. |date=1988 |title=Midland Through the Peak: A Pictorial History of the Midland Railway Main Line Routes Between Derby and Manch |publisher=Unicorn Books |isbn=1852410019}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|New Mills Central railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|NMC|SK223JB}}\n*[http://www.railbrit.co.uk/location.php?loc=New%20Mills%20Central RAILSCOT - New Mills Central]\n\n{{Derbyshire stations}}\n{{High Peak}}\n{{coord|53.365|N|2.006|W|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central and Midland Joint Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1865]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:New Mills]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak, Derbyshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Mills_Central_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Jimmie Ireland", "text_new": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Jimmie Ireland\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = James Cecil Hardin Ireland\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1903|12|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date =  {{Death date and age |1998|10|25|1903|12|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Polmont]], [[Scotland]]\n| height =\n| weight =\n| ru_position = [[Hooker (rugby union)|Hooker]]\n| ru_amateuryears = -\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Glasgow HSFP]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = 1924\n| ru_province = [[Glasgow District (rugby union)|Glasgow District]]\n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland national under-16 rugby union team|Scotland U16]]<br/>[[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]<br/>[[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]]\n| ru_nationalyears = <br/>1925-27<br/>1936\n| ru_nationalcaps = <br/>11\n| ru_nationalpoints = <br/>(0)\n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs =\n| ru_coachyears =\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = 1938-39\n| ru_refereecomps = [[1938 Home Nations Championship|Home Nations]]\n| ru_refereeapps = 5\n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 1950\n   | term_end      = 1951\n   | predecessor        = [[Hamish Shaw]]\n   | successor          = [[Dan Drysdale]]\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 64th\n }}\n}}\n'''Jimmie Ireland''' (10 December 1903 - 25 October 1998) was a [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] international [[rugby union]] player. He became the 64th [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]].<ref>http://en.espn.co.uk/scotland/rugby/player/3225.html</ref>\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nIreland was born in Sauchiehall Street and went to Garnethill Primary. He then attended Glasgow High School.\n\nHe played for [[Glasgow HSFP]].<ref>The Essential History of Rugby Union: Scotland. Nick Oswald and John Griffiths. Headline Publishing. 2003</ref>\n\nThe Jimmie Ireland stand at the Glasgow club was opened in 2000.<ref>http://www.ghscl.org.uk/index.php/facilities/the-memorial-pavilion/81-ghscl/facilities/77-the-jimmie-ireland-stand</ref>\n\n===Provincial career===\n\nHe played for [[Glasgow District (rugby union)|Glasgow District]] in the 1924 inter-city match.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EphAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PKUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1945%2C4815645</ref>\n\n===International career===\n\nHe was capped at the age of 14 for Scotland Schools.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\nHe received ten caps for [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] from 1925 to 1927.<ref>http://en.espn.co.uk/statsguru/rugby/player/3225.html?class=1;template=results;type=player;view=match</ref>\n\nHe was the last surviving member of Scotland's first Grand Slam side of 1925. In 1996, he opened a block of hospitality suites at [[Murrayfield Stadium]] each one bearing a name of that famous XV.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\nHe swapped jerseys with Sam Tucker, the England hooker, after Scotland had beaten England at Twickenham in 1926. He was given a bill by the SRU for the loss of the Scotland jersey of 12 shillings and 6 pence.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\n===Referee career===\n\nHe was an international referee. He refereed 5 Home Nations Championship matches between 1938 and 1939.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nHe became President of [[Glasgow HSFP]].<ref>https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12250159.jimmie-ireland/</ref>\n\nHe was a Chairman of the International Rugby Board. As Chairman, in 1949, he saw that Australia, South Africa and New Zealand were admitted as full members for the first time.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\nHe was [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] for the period 1950 to 1951.<ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf|date=2018-08-16|title=Scottish Rugby Record 2018/19 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Outside of rugby==\n\nIreland was an accountant. An anecdote he often told at rugby dinners was the time he asked his boss for Saturday morning off as he was playing for Scotland at Murrayfield. His boss replied: 'What? The whole morning?'.<ref>https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12250159.jimmie-ireland/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ireland, Jimmie}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n[[Category:Scotland international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Glasgow HSFP players]]\n[[Category:Glasgow District players]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union referees]]\n[[Category:Barbarian F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Jimmie Ireland\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = James Cecil Hardin Ireland\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1903|12|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date =  {{Death date and age |1998|10|25|1903|12|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Polmont]], [[Scotland]]\n| height =\n| weight =\n| ru_position = [[Hooker (rugby union)|Hooker]]\n| ru_amateuryears = -\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Glasgow HSFP]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = 1924\n| ru_province = [[Glasgow District (rugby union)|Glasgow District]]\n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland national under-16 rugby union team|Scotland U16]]<br/>[[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]<br/>[[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]]\n| ru_nationalyears = <br/>1925-27<br/>1936\n| ru_nationalcaps = <br/>11\n| ru_nationalpoints = <br/>(0)\n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs =\n| ru_coachyears =\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = 1938-39\n| ru_refereecomps = [[1938 Home Nations Championship|Home Nations]]\n| ru_refereeapps = 5\n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 1950\n   | term_end      = 1951\n   | predecessor        = [[Hamish Shaw]]\n   | successor          = [[Dan Drysdale]]\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 64th\n }}\n}}\n'''Jimmie Ireland''' (10 December 1903 - 25 October 1998) was a [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] international [[rugby union]] player. He became the 64th [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]].<ref>http://en.espn.co.uk/scotland/rugby/player/3225.html</ref>\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nIreland was born in Sauchiehall Street and went to Garnethill Primary. He then attended Glasgow High School.\n\nHe played for [[Glasgow HSFP]].<ref>The Essential History of Rugby Union: Scotland. Nick Oswald and John Griffiths. Headline Publishing. 2003</ref>\n\nThe Jimmie Ireland stand at the Glasgow club was opened in 2000.<ref>http://www.ghscl.org.uk/index.php/facilities/the-memorial-pavilion/81-ghscl/facilities/77-the-jimmie-ireland-stand</ref>\n\n===Provincial career===\n\nHe played for [[Glasgow District (rugby union)|Glasgow District]] in the 1924 inter-city match.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EphAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PKUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1945%2C4815645</ref>\n\n===International career===\n\nHe was capped at the age of 14 for Scotland Schools.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\nHe received ten caps for [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] from 1925 to 1927.<ref>http://en.espn.co.uk/statsguru/rugby/player/3225.html?class=1;template=results;type=player;view=match</ref>\n\nHe was the last surviving member of Scotland's first Grand Slam side of 1925. In 1996, he opened a block of hospitality suites at [[Murrayfield Stadium]] each one bearing a name of that famous XV.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\nHe swapped jerseys with Sam Tucker, the England hooker, after Scotland had beaten England at Twickenham in 1926. He was given a bill by the SRU for the loss of the Scotland jersey of 12 shillings and 6 pence.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\n===Referee career===\n\nHe was an international referee. He refereed 5 Home Nations Championship matches between 1938 and 1939.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nHe became President of [[Glasgow HSFP]].<ref>https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12250159.jimmie-ireland/</ref>\n\nHe was a Chairman of the International Rugby Board. As Chairman, in 1949, he saw that Australia, South Africa and New Zealand were admittted as full members for the first time.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-jimmie-ireland-1187529.html</ref>\n\nHe was [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] for the period 1950 to 1951.<ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf|date=2018-08-16|title=Scottish Rugby Record 2018/19 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Outside of rugby==\n\nIreland was an accountant. An anecdote he often told at rugby dinners was the time he asked his boss for Saturday morning off as he was playing for Scotland at Murrayfield. His boss replied: 'What? The whole morning?'.<ref>https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12250159.jimmie-ireland/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ireland, Jimmie}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n[[Category:Scotland international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Glasgow HSFP players]]\n[[Category:Glasgow District players]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union referees]]\n[[Category:Barbarian F.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdministrative career:clean up,typo(s) fixed: ittted \u2192 itted", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmie_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Buxton railway station", "text_new": "{{about||the former Midland Railway station in Buxton, Derbyshire|Buxton (Midland) railway station|the station in Norfolk|Buxton railway station (Norfolk)}}\n{{short description|Railway station in Derbyshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name         = Buxton\n| code         = BUX\n| dft_category = E\n| image_name   = Buxton Station on a dull day - geograph.org.uk - 1770154.jpg\n| manager      = [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]\n| locale       = [[Buxton]]\n| borough      = [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]]\n<!-- | usage0405    = {{pad|1em}}0.225\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.261\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.264\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 0.284\n| usage0809    = {{increase}} 0.301\n| usage0910    = {{steady}} 0.301\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 0.309\n| usage1112    = {{decrease}} 0.298\n| usage1213    = {{decrease}} 0.289\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 0.290 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 0.324\n| usage1516    = {{increase}} 0.329\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 0.331\n| usage1718    = {{increase}} 0.332\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 0.346\n| platforms    = 2\n| symbol       = rail\n| caption      = A [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]] and a [[British Rail Class 150|Class 150/2]] unit at Buxton station\n| owner        = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.261|-1.913|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref      = SK059737\n| original     = [[Stockport, Disley and Whaley Bridge Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[London and North Western Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n| years        = {{start date|1863|06|15|df=y}}\n| events       = Station opened\n}}\n'''Buxton railway station''' serves the town of [[Buxton]] in [[Derbyshire]], England. It is managed and served by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]. The station is {{convert|25+3/4|mi|km}} south east of [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly]] and is the terminus of the [[Buxton Line]].\n\n==Facilities==\nThe station is fully staffed, with the ticket office open on weekdays between 05:50 - 20:00, Saturdays 05:50 - 20:00 and Sundays 08:15 - 22:30.  A self-service ticket machine is also available for use outside these times and for collecting pre-paid tickets.  A payphone, waiting room and toilets are all provided in the main building, whilst platform 1 has a waiting shelter and bench seating. Train running details are offered via automatic announcements, CIS displays and timetable poster boards.  Step-free access is available to both platforms from the main entrance.<ref>[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/bux/details.html Buxton station facilities] ''National Rail Enquiries''; Retrieved 17 May 2017</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nUntil May 2018, there was an hourly service daily (including Sundays) between Buxton and Manchester Piccadilly, taking about one hour. The service frequency was enhanced to about half-hourly in the morning and evening peaks. A limited number of trains worked through beyond Manchester, with trains to/from {{stnlnk|Blackpool North}}, [[Clitheroe railway station|Clitheroe]], {{stnlnk|Barrow-in-Furness}}, {{stnlnk|Wigan North Western}}, {{rws|Preston}} and {{stnlnk|Kirkby}}.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2017|86}}</ref>\n\nFrom 21 May 2018, two trains per hour started running between Manchester and Buxton all day, one of which omits certain stations en route. The evening and Sunday service remains hourly and there are no longer any through trains to/from destinations north of Manchester.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2018|86}}</ref>\n\nPlatform 2 is the main platform for arrivals and departures. Platform 1 is a departure platform by shunt move, which is usually used in early mornings by the first trains of the day which have been stabled overnight or when attachment/detachment of a unit to/from a formation is required.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n== Future ==\n\nNetwork Rail has proposed, in their North West RUS, installing a facing cross-over which will allow platform 1 to become fully operational as an arrival and departure platform. Doing this will reduce the number of shunt moves.\n\n== History ==\nTwo railways arrived in Buxton almost simultaneously in 1863. The [[Stockport, Disley and Whaley Bridge Railway]], heavily promoted by the [[London and North Western Railway|LNWR]], built its line from [[Manchester]] to [[Whaley Bridge railway station|Whaley Bridge]] and extended it to Buxton. Meanwhile, the [[Midland Railway]] extended the [[Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway]] from [[Rowsley]]. When the Midland extended its main line to [[New Mills]] in 1867, to bypass the LNWR, Buxton became a branch line from [[Millers Dale railway station|Millers Dale]]. The stations were side by side, with identical frontages designed by J. Smith with guidance from [[Joseph Paxton]], each having a [[wrought iron]] glazed [[train shed]].\n\nThe Midland station closed in 1967, along with the line to Rowsley, and the site is now a roadway. However, the line through [[Dove Holes Tunnel]] from Chinley is still used for freight, such as [[limestone]] from [[Tunstead, Derbyshire|Tunstead]], along with the old Midland branch into Buxton and part of the old [[Ashbourne Line]] (closed to passengers in October 1954), which remains in use to serve a lime works at Dowlow and the quarry at Hindlow.  These both join the main line just outside the station, where there also a number of sidings to allow trains to reverse.  The bay platform formerly used by Ashbourne line trains and the connecting curve from it towards Dowlow have been removed, though it is still possible to trace its route.  The LNWR station now handles local trains into Manchester, using its line through [[Dove Holes railway station|Dove Holes]] and [[Chapel-en-le-Frith railway station|Chapel-en-le-Frith]]. The surviving LNWR fan window has been restored and the external stonework cleaned.\n\n=== Accidents ===\n* A runaway limestone train demolished the boiler room and gents toilet and damaged the porters' room in 1897, killing a passenger and injuring a porter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://edition.pagesuite-professional.co.uk//html5/reader/production/default.aspx?&edid=7b86f0f7-498d-4a9a-aa51-b450bfa24a8f|title=What the railways are doing|last=|first=|date=September 1897|website=|publisher=Railway Magazine|pages=282|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> \n* A [[LNWR Class B]] [[Boiler explosion#Locomotive boiler explosions in the UK|boiler blew up]] in the station yard in 1921, killing the driver and fireman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=397|title=Accident at Buxton on 11th November 1921 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Buxton Railway Station LNWR Fan Window 17.09.2016R.jpg|London & North Western Railway Co fan window after restoration\nFile:Buxton railway station (Derbyshire) in 1978.jpg|[[British Rail Class 104|BR Class 104]] [[Diesel Multiple Unit|DMU]] in the snow, 24 December 1978\nFile:Buxton railway station 1958012 9600359f.jpg|Station exterior in 1965. The present station is on the left, and the former [[Midland Railway]] station, now closed, is in the centre of the picture.\nFile:Buxton LNWR Signal Box 17.09.2016.jpg|Buxton LNWR station signal box\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Radford, B., (1988) ''Midland Though The Peak'' Unicorn Books\n* Pevsner, Nikolaus (1953) (revised Elizabeth Williamson 1978). ''The Buildings of England: Derbyshire''. Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-14-071008-6}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{commons category|Buxton railway station}}\n{{stn art lrnk|BUX|SK176GL}}\n*[http://viewfinder.english-heritage.org.uk/search/reference.asp?index=1&main_query=&theme=&period=&county=&district=&place_name=buxton&imageUID=74195 English Heritage \u2013 Buxton station frontage]\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=National Rail}}\n{{s-rail-national|toc=Northern|route=[[Buxton line]]|next=Dove Holes}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Derbyshire stations}}\n{{High Peak}}\n\n[[Category:Buxton|Station]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Former London and North Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1863]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the former Midland Railway station in Buxton, Derbyshire|Buxton (Midland) railway station|the station in Norfolk|Buxton railway station (Norfolk)}}\n{{short description|Railway station in Derbyshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name         = Buxton\n| code         = BUX\n| dft_category = E\n| image_name   = Buxton Station on a dull day - geograph.org.uk - 1770154.jpg\n| manager      = [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]\n| locale       = [[Buxton]]\n| borough      = [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]]\n<!-- | usage0405    = {{pad|1em}}0.225\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.261\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.264\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 0.284\n| usage0809    = {{increase}} 0.301\n| usage0910    = {{steady}} 0.301\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 0.309\n| usage1112    = {{decrease}} 0.298\n| usage1213    = {{decrease}} 0.289\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 0.290 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 0.324\n| usage1516    = {{increase}} 0.329\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 0.331\n| usage1718    = {{increase}} 0.332\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 0.346\n| platforms    = 2\n| symbol       = rail\n| caption      = A [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]] and a [[British Rail Class 150|Class 150/2]] unit at Buxton station\n| owner        = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53.261|-1.913|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref      = SK059737\n| original     = [[Stockport, Disley and Whaley Bridge Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[London and North Western Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n| years        = {{start date|1863|06|15|df=y}}\n| events       = Station opened\n}}\n'''Buxton railway station''' serves the town of [[Buxton]] in [[Derbyshire]], England. It is managed and served by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]. The station is {{convert|25+3/4|mi|km}} south east of [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly]] and is the terminus of the [[Buxton Line]].\n\n==Facilities==\nThe station is fully staffed, with the ticket office open on weekdays between 05:50 - 20:00, Saturdays 05:50 - 20:00 and Sundays 08:15 - 22:30.  A self-service ticket machine is also available for use outside these times and for collecting pre-paid tickets.  A payphone, waiting room and toilets are all provided in the main building, whilst platform 1 has a waiting shelter and bench seating. Train running details are offered via automatic announcements, CIS displays and timetable poster boards.  Step-free access is available to both platforms from the main entrance.<ref>[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/bux/details.html Buxton station facilities] ''National Rail Enquiries''; Retrieved 17 May 2017</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nUntil May 2018, there was an hourly service daily (including Sundays) between Buxton and Manchester Piccadilly, taking about one hour. The service frequency was enhanced to about half-hourly in the morning and evening peaks. A limited number of trains worked through beyond Manchester, with trains to/from {{stnlnk|Blackpool North}}, [[Clitheroe railway station|Clitheroe]], {{stnlnk|Barrow-in-Furness}}, {{stnlnk|Wigan North Western}}, {{rws|Preston}} and {{stnlnk|Kirkby}}.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2017|86}}</ref>\n\nFrom 21 May 2018, two trains per hour started running between Manchester and Buxton all day, one of which omits certain stations en route. The evening and Sunday service remains hourly and there are no longer any through trains to/from destinations north of Manchester.<ref>{{NRtimes|May 2018|86}}</ref>\n\nPlatform 2 is the main platform for arrivals and departures. Platform 1 is a departure platform by shunt move, which is usually used in early mornings by the first trains of the day which have been stabled overnight or when attachment/detachment of a unit to/from a formation is required.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n== Future ==\n\nNetwork Rail has proposed, in their North West RUS, installing a facing cross-over which will allow platform 1 to become fully operational as an arrival and departure platform. Doing this will reduce the number of shunt moves.\n\n== History ==\nTwo railways arrived in Buxton almost simultaneously in 1863. The [[Stockport, Disley and Whaley Bridge Railway]], heavily promoted by the [[London and North Western Railway|LNWR]], built its line from [[Manchester]] to [[Whaley Bridge railway station|Whaley Bridge]] and extended it to Buxton. Meanwhile, the [[Midland Railway]] extended the [[Manchester, Buxton, Matlock and Midlands Junction Railway]] from [[Rowsley]]. When the Midland extended its main line to [[New Mills]] in 1867, to bypass the LNWR, Buxton became a branch line from [[Millers Dale railway station|Millers Dale]]. The stations were side by side, with identical frontages designed by J. Smith with guidance from [[Joseph Paxton]], each having a [[wrought iron]] glazed [[train shed]].\n\nThe Midland station closed in 1967, along with the line to Rowsley, and the site is now a roadway. However, the line through [[Dove Holes Tunnel]] from Chinley is still used for freight, such as [[limestone]] from [[Tunstead, Derbyshire|Tunstead]], along with the old Midland branch into Buxton and part of the old [[Ashbourne Line]] (closed to passengers in October 1954), which remains in use to serve a lime works at Dowlow and the quarry at Hindlow.  These both join the main line just outside the station, where there also a number of sidings to allow trains to reverse.  The bay platform formerly used by Ashbourne line trains and the connecting curve from it towards Dowlow have been removed, though it is still possible to trace its route.  The LNWR station now handles local trains into Manchester, using its line through [[Dove Holes railway station|Dove Holes]] and [[Chapel-en-le-Frith railway station|Chapel-en-le-Frith]]. The surviving LNWR fan window has been restored and the external stonework cleaned.\n\n=== Accidents ===\n* A runaway limestone train demolished the boiler room and gents toilet and damaged the porters' room in 1897, killing a passenger and injuring a porter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://edition.pagesuite-professional.co.uk//html5/reader/production/default.aspx?&edid=7b86f0f7-498d-4a9a-aa51-b450bfa24a8f|title=What the railways are doing|last=|first=|date=September 1897|website=|publisher=Railway Magazine|pages=282|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> \n* A [[LNWR Class B]] [[Boiler explosion#Locomotive boiler explosions in the UK|boiler blew up]] in the station yard in 1921, killing the driver and fireman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/eventsummary.php?eventID=397|title=Accident at Buxton on 11th November 1921 :: The Railways Archive|website=www.railwaysarchive.co.uk|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Buxton Railway Station LNWR Fan Window 17.09.2016R.jpg|London & North Western Railway Co fan window after restoration\nFile:Buxton railway station (Derbyshire) in 1978.jpg|[[British Rail Class 104|BR Class 104]] [[Diesel Multiple Unit|DMU]] in the snow, 24 December 1978\nFile:Buxton railway station 1958012 9600359f.jpg|Station exterior in 1965. The present station is on the left, and the former [[Midland Railway]] station, now closed, is in the centre of the picture.\nFile:Buxton LNWR Signal Box 17.09.2016.jpg|Buxton LNWR station signal box\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Radford, B., (1988) ''Midland Though The Peak'' Unicorn Books\n* Pevsner, Nikolaus (1953) (revised Elizabeth Williamson 1978). ''The Buildings of England: Derbyshire''. Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-14-071008-6}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{commons category|Buxton railway station}}\n{{stn art lrnk|BUX|SK176GL}}\n*[http://viewfinder.english-heritage.org.uk/search/reference.asp?index=1&main_query=&theme=&period=&county=&district=&place_name=buxton&imageUID=74195 English Heritage \u2013 Buxton station frontage]\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=National Rail}}\n{{s-rail-national|toc=Northern|route=[[Buxton line]]|next=Dove Holes}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Derbyshire stations}}\n{{High Peak}}\n\n[[Category:Buxton|Station]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Former London and North Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1863]]\n[[Category:Northern franchise railway stations]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak, Derbyshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buxton_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "AFM Bahauddin Nasim", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = AFM Bahauddin Nasim\n| office = [[Jatiya Sangsad]] member from [[Madaripur-3]]\n| term_start = 2014\n| term_end = 2018\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1961|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Madaripur District]] ,  [[East Bengal]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Bangladesh Awami League]]\n| image = \n| spouse = Dr. Sultana Shamima Chowdhury\n| children = Plabon, Faiza\n| alma_mater = [[Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University]]\n| native_name = \u0986. \u09ab. \u09ae. \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09be\u0989\u09a6\u09cd\u09a6\u09bf\u09a8 \u09a8\u09be\u099b\u09bf\u09ae\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| office2 = Joint Secretary of [[Awami League]]\n}}\n'''AFM Bahauddin Nasim'''(\u0986.\u09ab.\u09ae \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09be\u0989\u09a6\u09cd\u09a6\u09bf\u09a8 \u09a8\u09be\u099b\u09bf\u09ae) is a [[Bangladesh Awami League]] politician and former Member of Parliament from [[Madaripur-3]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.gov.bd/index.php/mps/members-of-parliament/current-mp-s/242-2013-06-23-09-36-47/mps-of-10th-parliament/2763-constituency-220-10th-en|title=Constituency 220_10th_En|website=www.parliament.gov.bd|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNasim was born on 11 November 1961. He has a Bachelor of Science degree from [[Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=A.F.M. Bahauddin (Nasim) Biography |url=https://amarmp.com/mp/649/biography |website=Amarmp |accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNasim started his political career by joining [[Bangladesh Chhatra League|Bangladesh Student League]]. He was president and also secretary of Bangladesh Student League [[Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University]] Unit. In 1981, he became president of Bangladesh Student League, [[Madaripur District]] unit. He was the President of the [[Bangladesh Awami Swechasebak League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bahauddin Nasim sent to jail after his surrender |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-63735 |accessdate=3 November 2018 |work=The Daily Star |date=17 November 2008 |language=en}}</ref> He was Assistant Personal Secretary -2 of\u00a0 Honorable [[Sheikh Hasina|Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina]] 1996-2001 period. He was elected to parliament in 2014 from Madaripur-3 as a Bangladesh Awami League candidate.<ref>{{cite news |title=A.F.M. Bahauddin (Nasim) History |url=https://amarmp.com/mp/649/history |accessdate=2 November 2018 |work=Amarmp}}</ref> In 2017, he was acquainted by a on a corruption case filed by the Anti-Corruption Commission.<ref>{{cite news |title=Awami League leader Bahauddin Nasim acquitted in ACC case |url=https://bdnews24.com/politics/2017/09/28/awami-league-leader-bahauddin-nasim-acquitted-in-acc-case |accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> He was a member of the treasury bench of the Parliament of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tea export fetches at Tk 17cr in last FY: Tofail |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/arcprint/details/145179/2018-04-10 |accessdate=3 November 2018 |work=theindependentbd.com |publisher=The Independent}}</ref> He is now Joint Secretary of [[Awami League|Bangladesh Awami League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelionline.com/%e0%a6%86%e0%a6%93%e0%a7%9f%e0%a6%be%e0%a6%ae%e0%a7%80-%e0%a6%b2%e0%a7%80%e0%a6%97%e0%a7%87%e0%a6%b0-%e0%a6%95%e0%a7%87%e0%a6%a8%e0%a7%8d%e0%a6%a6%e0%a7%8d%e0%a6%b0%e0%a7%80%e0%a7%9f-%e0%a6%95-3/|title=\u0986\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09ae\u09c0 \u09b2\u09c0\u0997\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u0995\u09ae\u09bf\u099f\u09bf\u09a4\u09c7 \u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be|date=2019-12-21|website=\u099a\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b2 \u0986\u0987 \u0985\u09a8\u09b2\u09be\u0987\u09a8|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAFM Bahauddin Nasim was born on November 11, 1961 in [[Madaripur District|Madaripur]], [[Faridpur District|Faridpur district]] of [[East Pakistan]]. Nasim is married to Dr. Sultana Shamima Chowdhury. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nasim, AFM Bahauddin}}\n[[Category:Bangladesh Awami League politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:10th Jatiya Sangsad members]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = AFM Bahauddin Nasim\n| office = [[Jatiya Sangsad]] member from [[Madaripur-3]]\n| term_start = 2014\n| term_end = 2018\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1961|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Madaripur District]] ,  [[East Bengal]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Bangladesh Awami League]]\n| image = \n| spouse = Dr. Sultana Shamima Chowdhury\n| children = Plabon, Faiza\n| alma_mater = [[Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University]]\n| native_name = \u0986. \u09ab. \u09ae. \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09be\u0989\u09a6\u09cd\u09a6\u09bf\u09a8 \u09a8\u09be\u099b\u09bf\u09ae\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| office2 = Joint Secretary of [[Awami League]]\n}}\n'''AFM Bahauddin Nasim'''(\u0986.\u09ab.\u09ae \u09ac\u09be\u09b9\u09be\u0989\u09a6\u09cd\u09a6\u09bf\u09a8 \u09a8\u09be\u099b\u09bf\u09ae) is a [[Bangladesh Awami League]] politician and former Member of Parliament from [[Madaripur-3]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.gov.bd/index.php/mps/members-of-parliament/current-mp-s/242-2013-06-23-09-36-47/mps-of-10th-parliament/2763-constituency-220-10th-en|title=Constituency 220_10th_En|website=www.parliament.gov.bd|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNasim was born on 11 November 1961. He has a Bachelor of Science degree from Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University.<ref>{{cite web |title=A.F.M. Bahauddin (Nasim) Biography |url=https://amarmp.com/mp/649/biography |website=Amarmp |accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNasim was the President of the  Awami Swechchhasebak League.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bahauddin Nasim sent to jail after his surrender |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-63735 |accessdate=3 November 2018 |work=The Daily Star |date=17 November 2008 |language=en}}</ref> He was Assistant Personal Secretary -2 of\u00a0 Honorable [[Sheikh Hasina|Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina]] 1996-2001 period. He was elected to parliament in 2014 from Madaripur-3 as a Bangladesh Awami League candidate.<ref>{{cite news |title=A.F.M. Bahauddin (Nasim) History |url=https://amarmp.com/mp/649/history |accessdate=2 November 2018 |work=Amarmp}}</ref> In 2017, he was acquainted by a on a corruption case filed by the Anti-Corruption Commission.<ref>{{cite news |title=Awami League leader Bahauddin Nasim acquitted in ACC case |url=https://bdnews24.com/politics/2017/09/28/awami-league-leader-bahauddin-nasim-acquitted-in-acc-case |accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> He was a member of the treasury bench of the Parliament of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tea export fetches at Tk 17cr in last FY: Tofail |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/arcprint/details/145179/2018-04-10 |accessdate=3 November 2018 |work=theindependentbd.com |publisher=The Independent}}</ref> He is now Joint Secretary of [[Awami League|Bangladesh Awami League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelionline.com/%e0%a6%86%e0%a6%93%e0%a7%9f%e0%a6%be%e0%a6%ae%e0%a7%80-%e0%a6%b2%e0%a7%80%e0%a6%97%e0%a7%87%e0%a6%b0-%e0%a6%95%e0%a7%87%e0%a6%a8%e0%a7%8d%e0%a6%a6%e0%a7%8d%e0%a6%b0%e0%a7%80%e0%a7%9f-%e0%a6%95-3/|title=\u0986\u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09ae\u09c0 \u09b2\u09c0\u0997\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cd\u09b0\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u0995\u09ae\u09bf\u099f\u09bf\u09a4\u09c7 \u09af\u09be\u09b0\u09be|date=2019-12-21|website=\u099a\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b2 \u0986\u0987 \u0985\u09a8\u09b2\u09be\u0987\u09a8|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nNasim is married to Dr. Sultana Shamima Chowdhury.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAU