h\u0101ka\u015byapa's Precedence to \u0100nanda in the R\u0101jag\u1e5bha Council |journal=Indogaku Bukkyogaku Kenkyu [Journal of Indian and Buddhist Studies] |volume=11 |issue=2 |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921034502/https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |pages=824{{en dash}}817 |archive-date=21 September 2018 |url-status=live|doi=10.4259/ibk.11.824 }}<!--some Japanese journals number their pages in reverse order-->\n* {{Citation |last1=Voros |first1=Sebastjan |title=Mahakashyapa's Smile: Language, Silence, and Mysticism |journal=Synthesis Philosophica |date=January 2014 |volume=58 |issue=2 |pages=387\u2013402 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191449/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649_Mahakashyapa's_Smile_Language_Silence_and_Mysticism |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Welter |first=A. |year=2000 |chapter=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa\u2019s Smile: Silent Transmission and the Kung-an (K\u014dan) Tradition |title=The K\u014dan: Texts and Contexts in Zen Buddhism |pages=75\u2013109 |editor1-last=Heine |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Wright |editor2-first=D.S. |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-802780-5}}\n* {{Citation |first=A. |last=Welter |editor1-last=Buswell|editor1-first=Robert E.|title=Lineage |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|date=2004|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA, [[Thomson Gale]]|volume=2 |pages=462\u2013463 <!-- |isbn=0-02-865720-9-->|isbn=978-0-02-865718-9}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Wilson |first1=L. |editor-last1=Holt |editor-first1=J. |editor-last2=Kinnard |editor-first2=J.N. |editor-last3=Walters |editor-first3=J.S. |year=2003 |chapter=Beggars Can Be Choosers: Mah\u0101kassapa as a Selective Eater of Offerings |title=Constituting Communities, Therav\u0101da Buddhism and the Religious Cultures of South and Southeast Asia |pages=57\u201370 |isbn=978-0-7914-8705-1}}\n* {{Citation |last=Wiltshire |first=M.G. |year=1983 |title=The\" Suicide\" Problem in the P\u0101li Canon |journal=Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies |pages=124\u2013140 |url=https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8609/2516 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217175753/https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8609/2516 |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Witanachchi |first1=C.|editor1-last=Malalasekera |editor1-first=G. P. |editor2-last=Weeraratne |editor2-first=W. G. |editor1-link=G. P. Malalasekera |title=\u0100nanda |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Buddhism |date=1965 |publisher=[[Government of Sri Lanka]] |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/231090852/Enceylopaedia-of-Buddhism-Vol-i |volume=1 |oclc=2863845613}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Zurcher |first1=Erik |editor1-last=Williams |editor1-first=Paul |title=Buddhism: Critical Concepts in Religious Studies, 8: Buddhism in China, East Asia, and Japan |date=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |chapter=Buddhist Influence on Early Taoism |isbn=0-415-33234-6 |page=378}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html Mah\u0101 Kassapa, Father of the Sangha], by Hellmuth Hecker, biography based on the [[Pali Canon|P\u0101li Canon]], revised and enlarged translation from Wissen und Wandel volume XXI, number 6, 1975, (German) by [[Nyanaponika]] Thera, The Wheel Publication No. 345, {{ISBN|955-24-0026-0}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190713140808/https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html archived here.]\n* [https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 ''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa''], hosted by Learning Religion, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191247/https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 archived here.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lineage (Buddhism)|Lineage of Buddhist patriarchs]]<br /><small>(According to the [[Zen]] schools of China and Japan)</small>|before=[[Gautama Buddha|\u015a\u0101kyamuni]]<br /><small>Beginning of the lineage</small>|after=[[Ananda]]|years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahakasyapa}}\n[[Category:Foremost disciples]]\n[[Category:Arhats]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Buddhist patriarchs]]\n[[Category:5th-century Buddhist monks]]\n", "name_user": "Vami IV", "label": "safe", "comment": "ditto", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mah%C4%81k%C4%81%C5%9Byapa"}
{"title_page": "Faderhead", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = Faderhead\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image                 = Faderhead e tropolis 2014 -29.jpg\n| image_size            = 200px\n| caption            = \n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]\n| genre = [[Electronic dance music|Electronic]], [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[Synthpop]]\n| years_active        = 2004\u2013present \n| label               =  [[Accession Records]], [[L-Tracks]], Not A Robot Records\n| associated_acts = Shaolyn<br/>Shawn Mierez\n| website                 = [http://www.faderhead.com/ www.faderhead.com]\n| current_members     = Faderhead<br/>\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| Live Musicians = J\u00f6rg L\u00fctkemeier, Joel Meyer\n| Past Live Musicians = Alex Montana, Christine LaGivree, Dr. T, Shaolyn, Chandler XL, Judith Dorn, Daniel Meyer, \"The Lord\" Marco Visconti\n}}\n\nSami Mark Yahya, professionally known by his stage name '''Faderhead''' is a [[Germans|German]] [[electronic music]] producer from [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]. His music is usually described as [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[Synthpop]] or [[Futurepop]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\n==History==\nAfter releasing the track \"The Protagonist\" as a one-off compilation entry on the Advanced Electronics Vol. 3, Faderhead received a deal with Accession Records/Indigo to release his debut album FH1 in 2006. Positive reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/reviews_comments.php?id=15922_0_17_0_C |title=Faderhead - FH1 (cd Accession Records) - review, free links at SIDE-LINE |publisher=Side-line.com |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnonstop.co.uk/product-view.php?productid=11668 |access-date=September 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714135931/http://www.musicnonstop.co.uk/product-view.php?productid=11668 |archive-date=July 14, 2009 }}</ref> made FH1 an instant debut-success with standout tracks like \"The Protagonist\", \"Vanish\" and \"O/H Scavenger\". The year progressed and saw Faderhead play shows alongside bands like [[Diary Of Dreams]], [[SITD]], Painbastard and others.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716065821/http://www.diaryofdreams.de/index2.php?section=dod01&lg=en&dod_news=old&Seite=4&Total=63 ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contribe.de/eng_index.shtml |title={ Contribe &#124; Booking & Promotion } |publisher=Contribe.de |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>\n\n2007 saw the release of the FH2 CD which featured the club hit \"Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois\". Faderhead released a music video for the track \"Girly Show\" and played festivals like [[Wave-Gotik-Treffen]] ([[Germany]]) and [[Infest (festival)|Infest]] ([[UK]]) among other shows.\n\n2008 started with the departure from Accession Records and the signing to L-Tracks Recordings. This decision led to serious speculation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=32491_0_2_0_C |title=Faderhead disillusioned by dark scene - calls it quits - Faderhead news at |publisher=Side-line.com |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> regarding the future of Faderhead by press and fans, but the free song/video release of the [[piano ballad]] \"Exit Ghost\" revealed that the project would continue. Only a few months later the [[club anthem]] \"TZDV\" was released, and on October 10, the FH3 album was released and again gathered top reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electrogothic.blogspot.com/2008/08/faderhead-fh3.html |access-date=September 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708034132/http://electrogothic.blogspot.com/2008/08/faderhead-fh3.html |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3785&Itemid=44 |access-date=September 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715170416/http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content |archive-date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gothtronic.com/?page=23&reviews=6290 |title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u043f\u043e \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0443 \u0448\u043e\u043f\u043f\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430 \u2013 \u0441\u043a\u0438\u0434\u043a\u0438, \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0436\u0438, \u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 - \u0412 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432 23 |publisher=Gothtronic.com |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Faderhead played the [[M'era Luna Festival]] (Germany), the [[Exit Festival]] ([[Serbia]]) as well as shows in the [[Netherlands]], [[Italy]], [[Greece]], [[Great Britain]], [[Belgium]] and [[Mexico]]. In October 2009, Faderhead released the \"Horizon Born\" EP, which was well received.<ref>[http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6077&Itemid=44 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715170416/http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6077&Itemid=44 |date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n2010 saw the release of ''Trilogy''. Since FH1, FH2 and FH3 had been sold out and were not reprinted, Faderhead decided to compile the most popular 18 tracks from that release onto one CD.\n\nIn October 2010, the fourth full-length album, ''Black Friday'', was released. The concept album tells the story of a night gone wrong. It was accompanied by a 15-minute short movie and quickly garnered reviews as Faderhead\u2019s most mature album.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130411184013/http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=8388&Itemid=44 ]</ref> Faderhead played a European club tour as well as the Christmas Ball Festival tour with Laibach, Project Pitchfork, Fields Of The Nephilim and Agonoize.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.madgoth.de/4990/news/the-christmas-ball-festival-2010-and-one-headliner-in-hannover |access-date=March 7, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609143245/http://www.madgoth.de/4990/news/the-christmas-ball-festival-2010-and-one-headliner-in-hannover |archive-date=June 9, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n2011 began with a 15-show tour in the USA with Aesthetic Perfection and Everything Goes Cold <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3uPnV_CQm0&list=PLx-21m_BTt0X0oUzr4oPyPC3cwX0RlZgf&index=5 |title=Faderhead - US Tour 2011 (Day 1 - Travel) |publisher=YouTube |date=2011-04-21 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> and ended with a download-only EP release called \u201cThe Way To Fuck Clubs\u201d, which showcased remixes of \u201cThe Way To Fuck God\u201d as well as an acoustic version of \u201cHot Bath And A Cold Razor\u201d and \u201cThe Moth And The Fire\u201d. The biggest show of 2011 happened at [[Wave-Gotik-Treffen]] in Leipzig when the festival organizers had to close the venue to prevent overcrowding.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7SHaFpcriPA&list=PLx-21m_BTt0X0oUzr4oPyPC3cwX0RlZgf&index=4 |title=Faderhead - 2011 Summer Festival Recap (Behind The Scenes) |publisher=YouTube |date=2011-09-27 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the fifth album, ''The World Of Faderhead'', was released alongside [https://web.archive.org/web/20131208105358/http://theworldoffaderhead.com/?p=visuals three 360\u00b0 panoramic images] and 3 music videos.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theworldoffaderhead.com |title=Faderhead - New Album! New Music Video! New Panoramic Image! |publisher=Theworldoffaderhead.com |date= |access-date=2014-07-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218104425/http://theworldoffaderhead.com/ |archive-date=2014-12-18 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The video to \u201cFistful Of Fuck You\u201d became popular, due to its original style and content. Faderhead headlined a 14-show US tour and played all over Europe including a set at the [[M'era Luna Festival]] hangar stage. The European pressing of \u201cThe World Of Faderhead\u201d was already almost sold out before the end of the year and Faderhead reached the no. 7 spot of MusicNonStop\u2019s best-selling releases of 2012 in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faderhead.com/blog/musicnonstop-top-sellers-2012/ |title=MusicNonStop Top Sellers 2012 \u2014 |publisher=Faderhead.com |date=2013-01-03 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> tying And One and coming in ahead of legacy-acts like Fields Of The Nephilim, De/Vision, Suicide Commando and Hocico. Because \"The World Of Faderhead\" sold out so quickly, Faderhead also released the double-CD-compilation \"Two Sides To Every Story\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stormingthebase.com/faderhead-two-sides-to-every-story-2cd/ |title=Faderhead. Two Sides To Every Story. 2CD. |publisher=Storming the Base |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> which features Faderhead's most popular clubtracks on CD 1 and the most popular pop-songs/ballads on CD 2.\n\n2013 saw Faderhead releasing the \"FH4\" album, which spawned the single and video to [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UR6ansmAkVo \"Dancers\"], a collaboration with Techno MC Shawn Mierez (\"I Like It Loud\") and Shaolyn (\"Face Down\"). Worldwide touring (including 14 shows in the US) followed and Faderhead returned to the Amphi Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amphi-festival.de/2013/archiv.html|title=Amphi Festival 2017 - Tanzbrunnen K\u00f6ln|last=GmbH|first=Amphi Festival|website=www.amphi-festival.de|language=de|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref> in K\u00f6ln/Germany.\n\nIn 2014 the \u201cAtoms & Emptiness\u201d-album was released in February. Faderhead went on a 4 week European co-headlining tour with Aesthetic Perfection and music videos to \u201cStand Up\u201d and \u201cWhen The Freaks Come Out\u201d were released. After that Faderhead took a 1.5 year break from producing and performing.\n\n2016 Faderhead released \u201cFH-X\u201d on February 12 and toured the UK and Germany. In October he also released the 10 song EP \u201cAnima In Machina\u201d[http://www.sonic-seducer.de/index.php/3163-faderhead-neue-ep-anima-in-machina-zum-download-kostenlos-anh%C3%B6ren.html] which featured 8 reworked old songs and 2 new tracks. Then Faderhead supported Covenant on a 10-show-tour in Germany which sold out venues in Hamburg, Hannover, Erfurt, Stuttgart, Krefeld and Frankfurt. The \"Anima In Machina\"-EP occupied the number 1 position in the German Alternative Charts (DAC)<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.deutsche-alternative-charts.de|title=Deutsche Alternative Charts - DAC - www.deutsche-alternative-charts.de|website=www.deutsche-alternative-charts.de|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref> for 6 weeks in a row.\n\n2017 opened with the release of the single \u201cKnow Your Darkness\u201d, a futurepop club song which debuted at number 1 in the German Alternative Charts (DAC).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe ninth studio album \"Night Physics\" (including the single \"Know Your Darkness\") was releases in late 2017 and reached number 1 in the German Alternative Charts (DAC)<ref name=\"auto\" />, followed by a 10-show-tour of Germany and a concert at the sold out Agra-Halle at Wave-Gotik-Treffen 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wave-gotik-treffen.de/|title=~ Offizielle Seiten Wave-Gotik-Treffen Leipzig ~|website=www.wave-gotik-treffen.de|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>. Faderhead then went on another tour of Germany with Project Pitchfork.\n\nIn 2019 Faderhead played the main stage at Amphi Festival in Cologne/Germany<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amphi-festival.de/|title=Amphi Festival 2020 - Tanzbrunnen K\u00f6ln|last=GmbH|first=Amphi Festival|website=www.amphi-festival.de|language=de|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> as well as NCN Festival in Deutzen<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monkeypress.de/2019/06/live/ankuendigungen/nocturnal-culture-night-2019-alle-bands-alle-infos/|title=NCN - NOCTURNAL CULTURE NIGHT 2019 - alle Bands, alle Infos|last=Meyer|first=Marius|date=2019-06-21|website=Monkeypress.de|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> briefly before the release of the tenth studio album \"Asteria\", which included the single \"From His Broken Bones\" that reached number 2 on the German Alternative Charts (DAC))<ref name=\"auto\" />. The band played an album release show at Kulttempel in Oberhausen/Germany<ref>{{Citation|title=Faderhead - Asteria Album Release Concert (Live)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gBHUx_qYzmI|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>.\n\nFaderhead's live shows are currently supported by either J\u00f6rg L\u00fctkemeier (formerly Straftanz) or Joe Meyer (formerly Project SAM) on keyboards and backing vocals. He has also previously been supported live by Daniel Meyer and G2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alternation.eu/faderhead,id,261,artysci.html|title=Faderhead|website=alternation.eu|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The Hamburg producer/vocalist uses different musicians for live performances and has collaborated on stage with musicians like Daniel Myer (Haujobb), Shawn \"Ultimate MC\" Mierez or with Marco Visconti (formerly [[XP8]]) - nicknamed \u201cThe Lord\u201d - as the longest standing member.\n\n<br />\n\n==Video game==\nA video game based on the music video for Fistful of Fuck You was created and released in 2014. The [[Beats of Rage]] game engine was used to program and run the game. Its design was based on images created by the music video's artists and programmed by Trev Nethers of the New York-based industrial band, Social Autopsy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://facebook.com/SocialAutopsy/ |title=Social Autopsy |publisher=facebook.com/socialautopsy |date= |accessdate=2018-03-07}}</ref> The game pays strict attention to the music video's content, allowing players to relive the music video first hand. It also includes playable characters, enemies and levels not featured in the music video. The game can be downloaded via Faderhead's official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faderhead.com/blog/fistful-of-fuck-you-the-video-game/ |title=Fistful Of Fuck You \u2013 The Video Game |publisher=Faderhead.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the game was re-released as Faderhead 2.0. The new release addressed bugs, balance issues, and animation problems. All new content was also added including new modes, playable characters and the ability to play the game with two players. Survival Mode allows the player to play as Nethers from Social Autopsy in a challenge to regain health by defeating enemies and absorbing their lifeforce. Music Video Mode is a modified version of Story Mode that plays exactly like the Music Video with shorter levels, fewer enemies and a new move set for the Faderhead character. Revenge Mode gives access to the boss characters in a reversal of Story Mode where you must stop Faderhead from playing his concert. Playable bosses include Andy from [[Combichrist]], Steve from [[And One]], Chris from [[Blutengel]], Graves from [[Aesthetic Perfection]] and Brian from [[The Gothsicles]]. Another new mode was also added, called Tournament Mode, which allows two to four players to compete against each other in a versus/fighting style of gameplay using all the playable characters from the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://facebook.com/FaderheadGame |title=Faderhead 2.0 |publisher=facebook.com/FaderheadGame |date= |accessdate=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n* 2006: ''[[FH1]]'' (Accession Records)\n* 2007: ''[[FH2]]'' (Accession Records)\n* 2008: ''[[FH3]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2010: ''[[Black Friday (Faderhead album)|Black Friday]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2012: ''[[The World of Faderhead]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2013: ''FH4'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2014: ''Atoms & Emptiness'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2016: ''FH-X'' (Not A Robot Records)\n* 2017: ''Night Physics''\n* 2019: ''Asteria''\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* 2010: ''[[Faderhead Trilogy|Trilogy]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2012: ''Two Sides To Every Story'' (2CD) (L-Tracks Recordings)\n\n===EPs===\n* 2009: ''[[Horizon Born]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2011: ''The Way to Fuck Clubs'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2013: ''Empires of the Northern Lights v2.42'' (Bandcamp)\n* 2015: ''The Tokyo Tapes'' (Bandcamp)\n* 2016: ''Anima In Machina'' (Not A Robot Records)\n* 2017: ''No Signal'' (Bandcamp)\n* 2019: ''Starchaser''\n\n===Singles===\n* 2004: \"The Protagonist\"\n* 2006: \"OH Scavenger vs. the Protagonist\"\n* 2006: \"Bassgod\"\n* 2008: \"Exit Ghost\"\n* 2010: \"69 Freaks Per Minute\"\n* 2013: \"Artificial Bullshit (Demo)\"\n* 2017: \"Know Your Darkness\"\n\n===Music videos===\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VNNLzpCaymI/ Girly Show]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V4GIZGoUyx4/ Exit Ghost]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sLptcBLy6Qw/ Tanz Zwo Drei Vier]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DG7P6NX8yyE/ Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (ft. Ultimate MC)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xTuLoWrxpe0/ Horizon Born (Electric Paradise Club Edit)]\n* [http://vimeo.com/17199798/ Black Friday (Short Movie)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fYQB4L3pxMc/ Destroy Improve Rebuild]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DND13niiVxU/ The Way to Fuck God]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ajlCLQqhiOg/ Fistful of Fuck You]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=quXNepYb4II/ Older Now]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_lNlHJWxZxE/ Inside of Me]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UR6ansmAkVo/ Dancers (ft.Shawn Mierez & Shaolyn)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Um5nVgw-NPU/ When the Freaks Come Out]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qGES2QBgFnw/ No Gods, No Flags, No Bullshit]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-Lzy8tSj5w Escape Gravity]\n\n===Free download MP3 releases===\n* Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (N64 Remix)\n* Going Home Alone (DDT Version)\n* [[In Bloom]] (Remix of the [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] Song)\n* [[Sexyback]] ([[Justin Timberlake]] Cover)\n* The Protagonist (Doctor Retroid's B-Movie Ride of Doom Remix)\n* [[White Wedding (song)|White Wedding]] ([[Billy Idol]] Cover)\n* White Room ([[Cream (band)|Cream]] Cover)\n* Living With Lions (Demo)\n* Death By Sushi\n\n===Compilation releases===\n* 2006: Accession Records Volume Three ('''Bassgod''')\n* 2006: Bestie:Mensch ('''Dirtygrrrls Dirtybois (Remix By [:[[SITD]]:])''' )\n* 2007: Extreme S\u00fcndenfall 6 ('''Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (Modulate Remix)''' )\n* 2007: Fxxk the Mainstream Vol. 1 ('''Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (Electro For the Masses Remix)''' )\n* 2009: Extreme S\u00fcndenfall 8 ('''TZDV (Club Version) ''')\n* 2009: Extreme S\u00fcndenfall 9 ('''Horizon Born (Electric Paradise Club Edit) ''')\n* 2010: Kinetik Festival Volume Three ('''69 Freaks Per Minute ''')\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.faderhead.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Faderhead}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:German musical groups]]\n[[Category:Electronic music groups]]\n[[Category:German industrial music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = Faderhead\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image                 = Faderhead e tropolis 2014 -29.jpg\n| image_size            = 200px\n| caption            = \n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]\n| genre = [[Electronic dance music|Electronic]], [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[Synthpop]]\n| years_active        = 2004\u2013present \n| label               =  [[Accession Records]], [[L-Tracks]], Not A Robot Records\n| associated_acts = Shaolyn<br/>Shawn Mierez\n| website                 = [http://www.faderhead.com/ www.faderhead.com]\n| current_members     = Faderhead<br/>\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| Live Musicians = J\u00f6rg L\u00fctkemeier, Joel Meyer\n| Past Live Musicians = Alex Montana, Christine LaGivree, Dr. T, Shaolyn, Chandler XL, Judith Dorn, Daniel Meyer, \"The Lord\" Marco Visconti\n}}\n\nSami Mark Yahya, professionally known by his stage name '''Faderhead''' is a [[Germans|German]] [[electronic music]] producer from [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]. His music is usually described as [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[Synthpop]] or [[Futurepop]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n\n==History==\nAfter releasing the track \"The Protagonist\" as a one-off compilation entry on the Advanced Electronics Vol. 3, Faderhead received a deal with Accession Records/Indigo to release his debut album FH1 in 2006. Positive reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/reviews_comments.php?id=15922_0_17_0_C |title=Faderhead - FH1 (cd Accession Records) - review, free links at SIDE-LINE |publisher=Side-line.com |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnonstop.co.uk/product-view.php?productid=11668 |access-date=September 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714135931/http://www.musicnonstop.co.uk/product-view.php?productid=11668 |archive-date=July 14, 2009 }}</ref> made FH1 an instant debut-success with standout tracks like \"The Protagonist\", \"Vanish\" and \"O/H Scavenger\". The year progressed and saw Faderhead play shows alongside bands like [[Diary Of Dreams]], [[SITD]], Painbastard and others.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716065821/http://www.diaryofdreams.de/index2.php?section=dod01&lg=en&dod_news=old&Seite=4&Total=63 ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contribe.de/eng_index.shtml |title={ Contribe &#124; Booking & Promotion } |publisher=Contribe.de |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>\n\n2007 saw the release of the FH2 CD which featured the club hit \"Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois\". Faderhead released a music video for the track \"Girly Show\" and played festivals like [[Wave-Gotik-Treffen]] ([[Germany]]) and [[Infest (festival)|Infest]] ([[UK]]) among other shows.\n\n2008 started with the departure from Accession Records and the signing to L-Tracks Recordings. This decision led to serious speculation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.side-line.com/news_comments.php?id=32491_0_2_0_C |title=Faderhead disillusioned by dark scene - calls it quits - Faderhead news at |publisher=Side-line.com |date=2013-11-27 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> regarding the future of Faderhead by press and fans, but the free song/video release of the [[piano ballad]] \"Exit Ghost\" revealed that the project would continue. Only a few months later the [[club anthem]] \"TZDV\" was released, and on October 10, the FH3 album was released and again gathered top reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electrogothic.blogspot.com/2008/08/faderhead-fh3.html |access-date=September 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708034132/http://electrogothic.blogspot.com/2008/08/faderhead-fh3.html |archive-date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3785&Itemid=44 |access-date=September 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715170416/http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content |archive-date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gothtronic.com/?page=23&reviews=6290 |title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u043f\u043e \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0443 \u0448\u043e\u043f\u043f\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430 \u2013 \u0441\u043a\u0438\u0434\u043a\u0438, \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0436\u0438, \u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 - \u0412 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432 23 |publisher=Gothtronic.com |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Faderhead played the [[M'era Luna Festival]] (Germany), the [[Exit Festival]] ([[Serbia]]) as well as shows in the [[Netherlands]], [[Italy]], [[Greece]], [[Great Britain]], [[Belgium]] and [[Mexico]]. In October 2009, Faderhead released the \"Horizon Born\" EP, which was well received.<ref>[http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6077&Itemid=44 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715170416/http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=6077&Itemid=44 |date=July 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n2010 saw the release of ''Trilogy''. Since FH1, FH2 and FH3 had been sold out and were not reprinted, Faderhead decided to compile the most popular 18 tracks from that release onto one CD.\n\nIn October 2010, the fourth full-length album, ''Black Friday'', was released. The concept album tells the story of a night gone wrong. It was accompanied by a 15-minute short movie and quickly garnered reviews as Faderhead\u2019s most mature album.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130411184013/http://www.reflectionsofdarkness.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=8388&Itemid=44 ]</ref> Faderhead played a European club tour as well as the Christmas Ball Festival tour with Laibach, Project Pitchfork, Fields Of The Nephilim and Agonoize.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.madgoth.de/4990/news/the-christmas-ball-festival-2010-and-one-headliner-in-hannover |access-date=March 7, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609143245/http://www.madgoth.de/4990/news/the-christmas-ball-festival-2010-and-one-headliner-in-hannover |archive-date=June 9, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n2011 began with a 15-show tour in the USA with Aesthetic Perfection and Everything Goes Cold <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3uPnV_CQm0&list=PLx-21m_BTt0X0oUzr4oPyPC3cwX0RlZgf&index=5 |title=Faderhead - US Tour 2011 (Day 1 - Travel) |publisher=YouTube |date=2011-04-21 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> and ended with a download-only EP release called \u201cThe Way To Fuck Clubs\u201d, which showcased remixes of \u201cThe Way To Fuck God\u201d as well as an acoustic version of \u201cHot Bath And A Cold Razor\u201d and \u201cThe Moth And The Fire\u201d. The biggest show of 2011 happened at [[Wave-Gotik-Treffen]] in Leipzig when the festival organizers had to close the venue to prevent overcrowding.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7SHaFpcriPA&list=PLx-21m_BTt0X0oUzr4oPyPC3cwX0RlZgf&index=4 |title=Faderhead - 2011 Summer Festival Recap (Behind The Scenes) |publisher=YouTube |date=2011-09-27 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the fifth album, ''The World Of Faderhead'', was released alongside [https://web.archive.org/web/20131208105358/http://theworldoffaderhead.com/?p=visuals three 360\u00b0 panoramic images] and 3 music videos.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theworldoffaderhead.com |title=Faderhead - New Album! New Music Video! New Panoramic Image! |publisher=Theworldoffaderhead.com |date= |access-date=2014-07-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218104425/http://theworldoffaderhead.com/ |archive-date=2014-12-18 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The video to \u201cFistful Of Fuck You\u201d became popular, due to its original style and content. Faderhead headlined a 14-show US tour and played all over Europe including a set at the [[M'era Luna Festival]] hangar stage. The European pressing of \u201cThe World Of Faderhead\u201d was already almost sold out before the end of the year and Faderhead reached the no. 7 spot of MusicNonStop\u2019s best-selling releases of 2012 in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faderhead.com/blog/musicnonstop-top-sellers-2012/ |title=MusicNonStop Top Sellers 2012 \u2014 |publisher=Faderhead.com |date=2013-01-03 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> tying And One and coming in ahead of legacy-acts like Fields Of The Nephilim, De/Vision, Suicide Commando and Hocico. Because \"The World Of Faderhead\" sold out so quickly, Faderhead also released the double-CD-compilation \"Two Sides To Every Story\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stormingthebase.com/faderhead-two-sides-to-every-story-2cd/ |title=Faderhead. Two Sides To Every Story. 2CD. |publisher=Storming the Base |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> which features Faderhead's most popular clubtracks on CD 1 and the most popular pop-songs/ballads on CD 2.\n\n2013 saw Faderhead releasing the \"FH4\" album, which spawned the single and video to [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UR6ansmAkVo \"Dancers\"], a collaboration with Techno MC Shawn Mierez (\"I Like It Loud\") and Shaolyn (\"Face Down\"). Worldwide touring (including 14 shows in the US) followed and Faderhead returned to the Amphi Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amphi-festival.de/2013/archiv.html|title=Amphi Festival 2017 - Tanzbrunnen K\u00f6ln|last=GmbH|first=Amphi Festival|website=www.amphi-festival.de|language=de|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref> in K\u00f6ln/Germany.\n\nIn 2014 the \u201cAtoms & Emptiness\u201d-album was released in February. Faderhead went on a 4 week European co-headlining tour with Aesthetic Perfection and music videos to \u201cStand Up\u201d and \u201cWhen The Freaks Come Out\u201d were released. After that Faderhead took a 1.5 year break from producing and performing.\n\n2016 Faderhead released \u201cFH-X\u201d on February 12 and toured the UK and Germany. In October he also released the 10 song EP \u201cAnima In Machina\u201d[http://www.sonic-seducer.de/index.php/3163-faderhead-neue-ep-anima-in-machina-zum-download-kostenlos-anh%C3%B6ren.html] which featured 8 reworked old songs and 2 new tracks. Then Faderhead supported Covenant on a 10-show-tour in Germany which sold out venues in Hamburg, Hannover, Erfurt, Stuttgart, Krefeld and Frankfurt. The \"Anima In Machina\"-EP occupied the number 1 position in the German Alternative Charts (DAC)<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.deutsche-alternative-charts.de|title=Deutsche Alternative Charts - DAC - www.deutsche-alternative-charts.de|website=www.deutsche-alternative-charts.de|access-date=2017-07-20}}</ref> for 6 weeks in a row.\n\n2017 opened with the release of the single \u201cKnow Your Darkness\u201d, a futurepop club song which debuted at number 1 in the German Alternative Charts (DAC).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe ninth studio album \"Night Physics\" (including the single \"Know Your Darkness\") was releases in late 2017 and reached number 1 in the German Alternative Charts (DAC)<ref name=\"auto\" />, followed by a 10-show-tour of Germany and a concert at the sold out Agra-Halle at Wave-Gotik-Treffen 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wave-gotik-treffen.de/|title=~ Offizielle Seiten Wave-Gotik-Treffen Leipzig ~|website=www.wave-gotik-treffen.de|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>. Faderhead then went on another tour of Germany with Project Pitchfork.\n\nIn 2019 Faderhead played the main stage at Amphi Festival in Cologne/Germany<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amphi-festival.de/|title=Amphi Festival 2020 - Tanzbrunnen K\u00f6ln|last=GmbH|first=Amphi Festival|website=www.amphi-festival.de|language=de|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> as well as NCN Festival in Deutzen<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monkeypress.de/2019/06/live/ankuendigungen/nocturnal-culture-night-2019-alle-bands-alle-infos/|title=NCN - NOCTURNAL CULTURE NIGHT 2019 - alle Bands, alle Infos|last=Meyer|first=Marius|date=2019-06-21|website=Monkeypress.de|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> briefly before the release of the tenth studio album \"Asteria\", which included the single \"From His Broken Bones\" that reached number 2 on the German Alternative Charts (DAC))<ref name=\"auto\" />. The band played an album release show at Kulttempel in Oberhausen/Germany<ref>{{Citation|title=Faderhead - Asteria Album Release Concert (Live)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gBHUx_qYzmI|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>.\n\nFaderhead's live shows are currently supported by either J\u00f6rg L\u00fctkemeier (formerly Straftanz) or Joe Meyer (formerly Project SAM) on keyboards and backing vocals. The Hamburg producer/vocalist uses different musicians for live performances and has collaborated on stage with musicians like Daniel Myer (Haujobb), Shawn \"Ultimate MC\" Mierez or with Marco Visconti (formerly [[XP8]]) - nicknamed \u201cThe Lord\u201d - as the longest standing member.\n\n<br />\n\n==Video game==\nA video game based on the music video for Fistful of Fuck You was created and released in 2014. The [[Beats of Rage]] game engine was used to program and run the game. Its design was based on images created by the music video's artists and programmed by Trev Nethers of the New York-based industrial band, Social Autopsy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://facebook.com/SocialAutopsy/ |title=Social Autopsy |publisher=facebook.com/socialautopsy |date= |accessdate=2018-03-07}}</ref> The game pays strict attention to the music video's content, allowing players to relive the music video first hand. It also includes playable characters, enemies and levels not featured in the music video. The game can be downloaded via Faderhead's official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faderhead.com/blog/fistful-of-fuck-you-the-video-game/ |title=Fistful Of Fuck You \u2013 The Video Game |publisher=Faderhead.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the game was re-released as Faderhead 2.0. The new release addressed bugs, balance issues, and animation problems. All new content was also added including new modes, playable characters and the ability to play the game with two players. Survival Mode allows the player to play as Nethers from Social Autopsy in a challenge to regain health by defeating enemies and absorbing their lifeforce. Music Video Mode is a modified version of Story Mode that plays exactly like the Music Video with shorter levels, fewer enemies and a new move set for the Faderhead character. Revenge Mode gives access to the boss characters in a reversal of Story Mode where you must stop Faderhead from playing his concert. Playable bosses include Andy from [[Combichrist]], Steve from [[And One]], Chris from [[Blutengel]], Graves from [[Aesthetic Perfection]] and Brian from [[The Gothsicles]]. Another new mode was also added, called Tournament Mode, which allows two to four players to compete against each other in a versus/fighting style of gameplay using all the playable characters from the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://facebook.com/FaderheadGame |title=Faderhead 2.0 |publisher=facebook.com/FaderheadGame |date= |accessdate=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n* 2006: ''[[FH1]]'' (Accession Records)\n* 2007: ''[[FH2]]'' (Accession Records)\n* 2008: ''[[FH3]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2010: ''[[Black Friday (Faderhead album)|Black Friday]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2012: ''[[The World of Faderhead]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2013: ''FH4'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2014: ''Atoms & Emptiness'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2016: ''FH-X'' (Not A Robot Records)\n* 2017: ''Night Physics''\n* 2019: ''Asteria''\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* 2010: ''[[Faderhead Trilogy|Trilogy]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2012: ''Two Sides To Every Story'' (2CD) (L-Tracks Recordings)\n\n===EPs===\n* 2009: ''[[Horizon Born]]'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2011: ''The Way to Fuck Clubs'' (L-Tracks Recordings)\n* 2013: ''Empires of the Northern Lights v2.42'' (Bandcamp)\n* 2015: ''The Tokyo Tapes'' (Bandcamp)\n* 2016: ''Anima In Machina'' (Not A Robot Records)\n* 2017: ''No Signal'' (Bandcamp)\n* 2019: ''Starchaser''\n\n===Singles===\n* 2004: \"The Protagonist\"\n* 2006: \"OH Scavenger vs. the Protagonist\"\n* 2006: \"Bassgod\"\n* 2008: \"Exit Ghost\"\n* 2010: \"69 Freaks Per Minute\"\n* 2013: \"Artificial Bullshit (Demo)\"\n* 2017: \"Know Your Darkness\"\n\n===Music videos===\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VNNLzpCaymI/ Girly Show]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V4GIZGoUyx4/ Exit Ghost]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sLptcBLy6Qw/ Tanz Zwo Drei Vier]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DG7P6NX8yyE/ Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (ft. Ultimate MC)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xTuLoWrxpe0/ Horizon Born (Electric Paradise Club Edit)]\n* [http://vimeo.com/17199798/ Black Friday (Short Movie)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fYQB4L3pxMc/ Destroy Improve Rebuild]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DND13niiVxU/ The Way to Fuck God]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ajlCLQqhiOg/ Fistful of Fuck You]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=quXNepYb4II/ Older Now]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_lNlHJWxZxE/ Inside of Me]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UR6ansmAkVo/ Dancers (ft.Shawn Mierez & Shaolyn)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Um5nVgw-NPU/ When the Freaks Come Out]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qGES2QBgFnw/ No Gods, No Flags, No Bullshit]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z-Lzy8tSj5w Escape Gravity]\n\n===Free download MP3 releases===\n* Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (N64 Remix)\n* Going Home Alone (DDT Version)\n* [[In Bloom]] (Remix of the [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] Song)\n* [[Sexyback]] ([[Justin Timberlake]] Cover)\n* The Protagonist (Doctor Retroid's B-Movie Ride of Doom Remix)\n* [[White Wedding (song)|White Wedding]] ([[Billy Idol]] Cover)\n* White Room ([[Cream (band)|Cream]] Cover)\n* Living With Lions (Demo)\n* Death By Sushi\n\n===Compilation releases===\n* 2006: Accession Records Volume Three ('''Bassgod''')\n* 2006: Bestie:Mensch ('''Dirtygrrrls Dirtybois (Remix By [:[[SITD]]:])''' )\n* 2007: Extreme S\u00fcndenfall 6 ('''Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (Modulate Remix)''' )\n* 2007: Fxxk the Mainstream Vol. 1 ('''Dirtygrrrls/Dirtybois (Electro For the Masses Remix)''' )\n* 2009: Extreme S\u00fcndenfall 8 ('''TZDV (Club Version) ''')\n* 2009: Extreme S\u00fcndenfall 9 ('''Horizon Born (Electric Paradise Club Edit) ''')\n* 2010: Kinetik Festival Volume Three ('''69 Freaks Per Minute ''')\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.faderhead.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Faderhead}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:German musical groups]]\n[[Category:Electronic music groups]]\n[[Category:German industri